# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: robotics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] In robot kinematics, **forward kinematics** refers to the use of the kinematic equations of a robot to compute the position of the end-effector from specified values for the joint parameters.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] The kinematics equations of the robot are used in robotics, computer games, and animation.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] The reverse process, that computes the joint parameters that achieve a specified position of the end-effector, is known as inverse kinematics.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] The kinematics equations for the series chain of a robot are obtained using a rigid transformation [Z] to characterize the relative movement allowed at each joint and separate rigid transformation [X] to define the dimensions of each link.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] where [T] is the transformation locating the end-link.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] These equations are called the kinematics equations of the serial chain.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] In 1955, Jacques Denavit and Richard Hartenberg introduced a convention for the definition of the joint matrices [Z] and link matrices [X] to standardize the coordinate frame for spatial linkages.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] where *θi*, *di*, *αi,i+1* and *ai,i+1* are known as the Denavit-Hartenberg parameters.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] where ${}^{i-1}T_{i}(\theta _{i})$ is the transformation matrix from the frame of link i to link $i-1$ .
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] In robotics, these are conventionally described by Denavit–Hartenberg parameters.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] The forward kinematic equations can be used as a method in 3D computer graphics for animating models.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] The essential concept of forward kinematic animation is that the positions of particular parts of the model at a specified time are calculated from the position and orientation of the object, together with any information on the joints of an articulated model.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] So for example if the object to be animated is an arm with the shoulder remaining at a fixed location, the location of the tip of the thumb would be calculated from the angles of the shoulder, elbow, wrist, thumb and knuckle joints.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] Three of these joints (the shoulder, wrist and the base of the thumb) have more than one degree of freedom, all of which must be taken into account.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] If the model were an entire human figure, then the location of the shoulder would also have to be calculated from other properties of the model.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] Forward kinematic animation can be distinguished from inverse kinematic animation by this means of calculation - in inverse kinematics the orientation of articulated parts is calculated from the desired position of certain points on the model.
[src:robotics/forward-kinematics] It is also distinguished from other animation systems by the fact that the motion of the model is defined directly by the animator - no account is taken of any physical laws that might be in effect on the model, such as gravity or collision with other models.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] IK operations are computationally much more complex than forward kinematics, in which joint parameters are trigonometrically calculated to achieve the position and orientation of the chain's end.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] In robotics, inverse kinematics makes use of the kinematics equations to determine the joint parameters that provide a desired configuration (position and rotation) for each of the robot's end effectors.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] This is important because robot tasks are performed with the end effectors, while control effort applies to the joints.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Determining the movement of a robot so that its end effectors move from an initial configuration to a desired configuration is known as motion planning.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics transforms the motion plan into joint actuator trajectories for the robot.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Similar formulas determine the positions of the skeleton of an animated character that is to move in a particular way in a film, or of a vehicle such as a car or boat containing the camera which is shooting a scene of a film.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The movement of a kinematic chain, whether it is a robot or an animated character, is modeled by the kinematics equations of the chain.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] These equations define the configuration of the chain in terms of its joint parameters.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Forward kinematics uses the joint parameters to compute the configuration of the chain, and inverse kinematics reverses this calculation to determine the joint parameters that achieve a desired configuration.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Kinematic analysis is one of the first steps in the design of most industrial robots.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Kinematic analysis allows the designer to obtain information on the position of each component within the mechanical system.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] This information is necessary for subsequent dynamic analysis along with control paths.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics is an example of the kinematic analysis of a constrained system of rigid bodies, or kinematic chain.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The kinematic equations of a robot can be used to define the loop equations of a complex articulated system.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] These loop equations are nonlinear constraints on the configuration parameters of the system.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The independent parameters in these equations are known as the degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] While analytical solutions to the inverse kinematics problem exist for a wide range of kinematic chains, computer modeling and animation tools often use Newton's method to solve the nonlinear kinematics equations.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] When trying to find an analytical solution it is often convenient to exploit the geometry of the system and decompose it using subproblems with known solutions.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Other applications of inverse kinematic algorithms include interactive manipulation, animation control and collision avoidance.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Inverse kinematics is important to game programming and 3D animation, where it is used to connect game characters physically to the world, such as feet landing firmly on top of terrain.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] An animated figure is modeled with a skeleton of rigid segments connected with joints, called a kinematic chain.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The kinematics equations of the figure define the relationship between the joint angles of the figure and its pose or configuration.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The forward kinematic animation problem uses the kinematics equations to determine the pose given the joint angles.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The *inverse kinematics problem* computes the joint angles for a desired pose of the figure.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] It is often easier for computer-based designers, artists, and animators to define the spatial configuration of an assembly or figure by moving parts, or arms and legs, rather than directly manipulating joint angles.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Therefore, inverse kinematics is used in computer-aided design systems to animate assemblies and by computer-based artists and animators to position figures and characters.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The assembly is modeled as rigid links connected by joints that are defined as mates, or geometric constraints.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Movement of one element requires the computation of the joint angles for the other elements to maintain the joint constraints.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] For example, inverse kinematics allows an artist to move the hand of a 3D human model to a desired position and orientation and have an algorithm select the proper angles of the wrist, elbow, and shoulder joints.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Successful implementation of computer animation usually also requires that the figure move within reasonable anthropomorphic limits.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] A method of comparing both forward and inverse kinematics for the animation of a character can be defined by the advantages inherent to each.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] For instance, blocking animation where large motion arcs are used is often more advantageous in forward kinematics.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] However, more delicate animation and positioning of the target end effector in relation to other models might be easier using inverted kinematics.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Modern digital creation packages (DCC) offer methods to apply both forward and inverse kinematics to models.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] In some, but not all cases, there exist analytical solutions to inverse kinematic problems.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] One such example is for a robot with 6 degrees of freedom (DOF) (for example, 6 revolute joints) moving in 3D space (with 3-position DOF, and 3 rotational DOF).
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] If the DOF of the robot equals or exceeds that of the end effector, for example with a 7-DoF robot with 7 revolute joints, then there exist infinitely many solutions to the IK problem and an analytical solution does not exist.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Further extending this example, it is possible to fix one joint and analytically solve for the other joints, but a better solution is perhaps offered by numerical methods, which can instead optimize a solution given additional preferences (costs in an optimization problem).
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] An analytic solution to an inverse kinematics problem is a closed-form expression that takes the end-effector pose as input and gives joint positions as output, $q=f(x)$ .
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Analytical inverse kinematics solvers can be significantly faster than numerical solvers and provide more than one solution, but only a finite number of solutions, for a given end-effector pose.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Many different programs (Such as FOSS programs IKFast and Inverse Kinematics Library) are able to solve these problems quickly and efficiently using different algorithms such as the FABRIK solver.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] One issue with these solvers, is that they are known to not necessarily give locally smooth solutions between two adjacent configurations, which can cause instability if iterative solutions to inverse kinematics are required, such as if the IK is solved inside a high-rate control loop.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Many industrial 6DOF robots feature three rotational joints with intersecting axes ("spherical wrist").
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] These robots, known as robots with an "Ortho-parallel Basis and a Spherical Wrist," can be defined by 7 kinematic parameters that are distances in their assumed standard geometry.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] These robots may have up to 8 independent solutions for any given position and rotation of the robot tool head.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Open-source solutions for C++ and Rust exist.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] OPW has also been integrated into ROS framework.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] There are many methods of modelling and solving inverse kinematics problems.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The most flexible of these methods typically rely on iterative optimization to seek out an approximate solution, due to the difficulty of inverting the forward kinematics equation and the possibility of an empty solution space.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The core idea behind several of these methods is to model the forward kinematics equation using a Taylor series expansion, which can be simpler to invert and solve than the original system.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The Jacobian inverse technique is a simple yet effective way of implementing inverse kinematics.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Let there be m variables that govern the forward-kinematics equation, i.e. the position function.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] These variables may be joint angles, lengths, or other arbitrary real values.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] If, for example, the IK system lives in a 3-dimensional space, the position function can be viewed as a mapping $p(x):\mathbb {R} ^{m}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The Jacobian inverse technique iteratively computes an estimate of $\Delta x$ that minimizes the error given by $||p(x_{0}+\Delta x_{\text{estimate}})-p_{1}||$ .
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] where $J_{p}(x_{0})$ is the (3 × m) Jacobian matrix of the position function at $x_{0}$ .
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] where $p_{i}(x)$ gives the i-th component of the position function, $x_{0,k}+h$ is simply $x_{0}$ with a small delta added to its k-th component, and h is a reasonably small positive value.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Applying the inverse Jacobian method once will result in a very rough estimate of the desired $\Delta x$ -vector.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] A line search should be used to scale this $\Delta x$ to an acceptable value.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Once some $\Delta x$ -vector has caused the error to drop close to zero, the algorithm should terminate.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] Existing methods based on the Hessian matrix of the system have been reported to converge to desired $\Delta x$ values using fewer iterations, though, in some cases more computational resources.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The inverse kinematics problem can also be approximated using heuristic methods.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] These methods perform simple, iterative operations to gradually lead to an approximation of the solution.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The heuristic algorithms have low computational cost (return the final pose very quickly), and usually support joint constraints.
[src:robotics/inverse-kinematics] The most popular heuristic algorithms are cyclic coordinate descent (CCD) and forward and backward reaching inverse kinematics (FABRIK).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] In this view, the viewer flies down to the rainforest canopy and flies through the virtual leaves.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This visualisation shows an airplane collecting a 50 km swathe of lidar data over the Brazilian rainforest.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] For ground-level features, colours range from deep brown to tan.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Vegetation heights are depicted in shades of green, where dark greens are closest to the ground and light greens are the highest.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar has terrestrial, airborne, and mobile uses.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It is commonly used to make high-resolution maps, with applications in surveying, geodesy, geomatics, archaeology, geography, geology, geomorphology, seismology, forestry, atmospheric physics, laser guidance, airborne laser swathe mapping (ALSM), and laser altimetry.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It is used to make digital 3-D representations of areas on the Earth's surface and ocean bottom of the intertidal and near coastal zone by varying the wavelength of light.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It has also been increasingly used in control and navigation for autonomous cars and for the helicopter *Ingenuity* on its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar has since been used extensively for atmospheric research and meteorology.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar instruments fitted to aircraft and satellites carry out surveying and mapping – a recent example being the U.S.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Geological Survey Experimental Advanced Airborne Research Lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] NASA has identified lidar as a key technology for enabling autonomous precision safe landing of future robotic and crewed lunar-landing vehicles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The essential concept of lidar was originated by E.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Synge in 1930, who envisaged the use of powerful searchlights to probe the atmosphere.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Under the direction of Malcolm Stitch, the Hughes Aircraft Company introduced the first lidar-like system in 1961, shortly after the invention of the laser.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Intended for satellite tracking, this system combined laser-focused imaging with the ability to calculate distances by measuring the time for a signal to return using appropriate sensors and data acquisition electronics.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It was originally called "Colidar" an acronym for "coherent light detecting and ranging", derived from the term "radar", itself an acronym for "radio detection and ranging".
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] All laser rangefinders, laser altimeters and lidar units are derived from the early colidar systems.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The first practical terrestrial application of a colidar system was the "Colidar Mark II", a large rifle-like laser rangefinder produced in 1963, which had a range of 11 km and an accuracy of 4.5 m, to be used for military targeting.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The first mention of lidar as a stand-alone word in 1963 suggests that it originated as a portmanteau of "light" and "radar": "Eventually the laser may provide an extremely sensitive detector of particular wavelengths from distant objects.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Meanwhile, it is being used to study the Moon by 'lidar' (light radar) ..." The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar's first applications were in meteorology, for which the National Center for Atmospheric Research used it to measure clouds and pollution.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The general public became aware of the accuracy and usefulness of lidar systems in 1971 during the Apollo 15 mission, when astronauts used a laser altimeter to map the surface of the Moon.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Although the English language no longer treats "radar" as an acronym, (i.e., uncapitalized), the word "lidar" was capitalized as "LIDAR" or "LiDAR" in some publications beginning in the 1980s.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Various publications refer to lidar as "LIDAR", "LiDAR", "LIDaR", or "Lidar".
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The USGS uses both "LIDAR" and "lidar", sometimes in the same document; the *New York Times* predominantly uses "lidar" for staff-written articles, although contributing news feeds such as Reuters may use Lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar uses ultraviolet, visible, or near infrared light to image objects.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It can target a wide range of materials, including non-metallic objects, rocks, rain, chemical compounds, aerosols, clouds and even single molecules.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A narrow laser beam can map physical features with very high resolutions; for example, an aircraft can map terrain at 30-centimetre (12 in) resolution or better.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Wavelengths vary to suit the target: from about 10 micrometers (infrared) to approximately 250 nanometers (ultraviolet).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Typically, light is reflected via backscattering, as opposed to pure reflection one might find with a mirror.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Different types of scattering are used for different lidar applications: most commonly Rayleigh scattering, Mie scattering, Raman scattering, and fluorescence.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Suitable combinations of wavelengths can allow remote mapping of atmospheric contents by identifying wavelength-dependent changes in the intensity of the returned signal.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar, although photonic radar more strictly refers to radio-frequency range finding using photonics components.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] where *c* is the speed of light, *d* is the distance between the detector and the object or surface being detected, and *t* is the time spent for the laser light to travel to the object or surface being detected, then travel back to the detector.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The two kinds of lidar detection schemes are "incoherent" or direct energy detection (which principally measures amplitude changes of the reflected light) and coherent detection (best for measuring Doppler shifts, or changes in the phase of the reflected light).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Coherent systems generally use optical heterodyne detection.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This is more sensitive than direct detection and allows them to operate at much lower power, but requires more complex transceivers.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Both types employ pulse models: either *micropulse* or *high energy*.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Micropulse systems utilize intermittent bursts of energy.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] They developed as a result of ever-increasing computer power, combined with advances in laser technology.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] They use considerably less energy in the laser, typically on the order of one microjoule, and are often "eye-safe", meaning they can be used without safety precautions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] 600–1,000 nm lasers are most common for non-scientific applications.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The maximum power of the laser is limited, or an automatic shut-off system which turns the laser off at specific altitudes is used in order to make it eye-safe for the people on the ground.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] One common alternative, 1,550 nm lasers, are eye-safe at relatively high power levels since this wavelength is strongly absorbed by water and barely reaches the retina, though camera sensors can still get damaged.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A trade-off though is that current detector technology is less advanced, so these wavelengths are generally used at longer ranges with lower accuracies.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] They are also used for military applications because 1,550 nm is not visible in night vision goggles, unlike the shorter 1,000 nm infrared laser.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Airborne topographic mapping lidars generally use 1,064 nm diode-pumped YAG lasers, while bathymetric (underwater depth research) systems generally use 532 nm frequency-doubled diode pumped YAG lasers because 532 nm penetrates water with much less attenuation than 1,064 nm.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Laser settings include the laser repetition rate (which controls the data collection speed).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Pulse length is generally an attribute of the laser cavity length, the number of passes required through the gain material (YAG, YLF, etc.), and Q-switch (pulsing) speed.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Better target resolution is achieved with shorter pulses, provided the lidar receiver detectors and electronics have sufficient bandwidth.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A phased array can illuminate any direction by using a microscopic array of individual antennas.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Controlling the timing (phase) of each antenna steers a cohesive signal in a specific direction.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Phased arrays have been used in radar since the 1940s.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] On the order of a million optical antennas are used to see a radiation pattern of a certain size in a certain direction.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] To achieve this the phase of each individual antenna (emitter) are precisely controlled.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It is very difficult, if possible at all, to use the same technique in a lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The main problems are that all individual emitters must be coherent (technically coming from the same "master" oscillator or laser source), have dimensions about the wavelength of the emitted light (1 micron range) to act as a point source with their phases being controlled with high accuracy.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Microelectromechanical mirrors (MEMS) are not entirely solid-state.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] However, their tiny form factor provides many of the same cost benefits.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A single laser is directed to a single mirror that can be reoriented to view any part of the target field.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] However, MEMS systems generally operate in a single plane (left to right).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] To add a second dimension generally requires a second mirror that moves up and down.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Alternatively, another laser can hit the same mirror from another angle.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] MEMS systems can be disrupted by shock/vibration and may require repeated calibration.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Image development speed is affected by the speed at which they are scanned.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Options to scan the azimuth and elevation include dual oscillating plane mirrors, a combination with a polygon mirror, and a dual axis scanner.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Optic choices affect the angular resolution and range that can be detected.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A hole mirror or a beam splitter are options to collect a return signal.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Two main photodetector technologies are used in lidar: solid-state photodetectors, such as silicon avalanche photodiodes, or photomultipliers.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The sensitivity of the receiver is another parameter that has to be balanced in a lidar design.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar sensors mounted on mobile platforms such as airplanes or satellites require instrumentation to determine the absolute position and orientation of the sensor.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Such devices generally include a Global Positioning System receiver and an inertial measurement unit (IMU).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar uses active sensors that supply their own illumination source.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The energy source hits objects and the reflected energy is detected and measured by sensors.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Distance to the object is determined by recording the time between transmitted and backscattered pulses and by using the speed of light to calculate the distance traveled.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Flash lidar allows for 3-D imaging because of the camera's ability to emit a larger flash and sense the spatial relationships and dimensions of area of interest with the returned energy.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This allows for more accurate imaging because the captured frames do not need to be stitched together, and the system is not sensitive to platform motion.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] 3-D imaging can be achieved using both scanning and non-scanning systems.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] "3-D gated viewing laser radar" is a non-scanning laser ranging system that applies a pulsed laser and a fast gated camera.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Research has begun for virtual beam steering using digital light processing (DLP) technology.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Imaging lidar can also be performed using arrays of high speed detectors and modulation sensitive detector arrays typically built on single chips using complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) and hybrid CMOS/charge-coupled device (CCD) fabrication techniques.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] In these devices each pixel performs some local processing such as demodulation or gating at high speed, downconverting the signals to video rate so that the array can be read like a camera.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Using this technique many thousands of pixels / channels may be acquired simultaneously.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] High resolution 3-D lidar cameras use homodyne detection with an electronic CCD or CMOS shutter.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A coherent imaging lidar uses synthetic array heterodyne detection to enable a staring single element receiver to act as though it were an imaging array.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] In 2014, Lincoln Laboratory announced a new imaging chip with more than 16,384 pixels, each able to image a single photon, enabling them to capture a wide area in a single image.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] An earlier generation of the technology with one fourth as many pixels was dispatched by the U.S. military after the January 2010 Haiti earthquake.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A single pass by a business jet at 3,000 m (10,000 ft) over Port-au-Prince was able to capture instantaneous snapshots of 600 m (2,000 ft) squares of the city at a resolution of 30 cm (1 ft), displaying the precise height of rubble strewn in city streets.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The new system is ten times better, and could produce much larger maps more quickly.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The chip uses indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs), which operates in the infrared spectrum at a relatively long wavelength that allows for higher power and longer ranges.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] In many applications, such as self-driving cars, the new system will lower costs by not requiring a mechanical component to aim the chip.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] InGaAs uses less hazardous wavelengths than conventional silicon detectors, which operate at visual wavelengths.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] New technologies for infrared single-photon counting lidar are advancing rapidly, including arrays and cameras in a variety of semiconductor and superconducting platforms.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar can be oriented to nadir, zenith, or laterally.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] For example, lidar altimeters look down, an atmospheric lidar looks up, and lidar-based collision avoidance systems are side-looking.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar applications can be divided into airborne and terrestrial types.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The two types require scanners with varying specifications based on the data's purpose, the size of the area to be captured, the range of measurement desired, the cost of equipment, and more.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Spaceborne platforms are also possible, see satellite laser altimetry.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar (also *airborne laser scanning*) is when a laser scanner, while attached to an aircraft during flight, creates a 3-D point cloud model of the landscape.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This is currently the most detailed and accurate method of creating digital elevation models, replacing photogrammetry.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] One major advantage in comparison with photogrammetry is the ability to filter out reflections from vegetation from the point cloud model to create a digital terrain model which represents ground surfaces such as rivers, paths, cultural heritage sites, etc., which are concealed by trees.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Within the category of airborne lidar, there is sometimes a distinction made between high-altitude and low-altitude applications, but the main difference is a reduction in both accuracy and point density of data acquired at higher altitudes.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar can also be used to create bathymetric models in shallow water.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The main constituents of airborne lidar include digital elevation models (DEM) and digital surface models (DSM).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The points and ground points are the vectors of discrete points while DEM and DSM are interpolated raster grids of discrete points.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The process also involves capturing of digital aerial photographs.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] To interpret deep-seated landslides for example, under the cover of vegetation, scarps, tension cracks or tipped trees airborne lidar is used.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar digital elevation models can see through the canopy of forest cover, perform detailed measurements of scarps, erosion and tilting of electric poles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar data is processed using a toolbox called Toolbox for Lidar Data Filtering and Forest Studies (TIFFS) for lidar data filtering and terrain study software.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The data is interpolated to digital terrain models using the software.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The laser is directed at the region to be mapped and each point's height above the ground is calculated by subtracting the original z-coordinate from the corresponding digital terrain model elevation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Based on this height above the ground the non-vegetation data is obtained which may include objects such as buildings, electric power lines, flying birds, insects, etc.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The rest of the points are treated as vegetation and used for modeling and mapping.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Within each of these plots, lidar metrics are calculated by calculating statistics such as mean, standard deviation, skewness, percentiles, quadratic mean, etc.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Multiple commercial lidar systems for unmanned aerial vehicles are currently on the market.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] These platforms can systematically scan large areas, or provide a cheaper alternative to manned aircraft for smaller scanning operations.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The airborne lidar bathymetric technological system involves the measurement of time of flight of a signal from a source to its return to the sensor.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The data acquisition technique involves a sea floor mapping component and a ground truth component that includes video transects and sampling.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] It works using a green spectrum (532 nm) laser beam.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Two beams are projected onto a fast rotating mirror, which creates an array of points.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] One of the beams penetrates the water and also detects the bottom surface of the water under favorable conditions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Water depth measurable by lidar depends on the clarity of the water and the absorption of the wavelength used.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Water is most transparent to green and blue light, so these will penetrate deepest in clean water.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Blue-green light of 532 nm produced by frequency doubled solid-state IR laser output is the standard for airborne bathymetry.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This light can penetrate water but pulse strength attenuates exponentially with distance traveled through the water.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Lidar can measure depths from about 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft), with vertical accuracy in the order of 15 cm (6 in).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The surface reflection makes water shallower than about 0.9 m (3 ft) difficult to resolve, and absorption limits the maximum depth.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Turbidity causes scattering and has a significant role in determining the maximum depth that can be resolved in most situations, and dissolved pigments can increase absorption depending on wavelength.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Other reports indicate that water penetration tends to be between two and three times Secchi depth.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Bathymetric lidar is most useful in the 0–10 m (0–33 ft) depth range in coastal mapping.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] On average in fairly clear coastal seawater lidar can penetrate to about 7 m (23 ft), and in turbid water up to about 3 m (10 ft).
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] An average value found by Saputra et al, 2021, is for the green laser light to penetrate water about one and a half to two times Secchi depth in Indonesian waters.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Water temperature and salinity have an effect on the refractive index which has a small effect on the depth calculation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The data obtained shows the full extent of the land surface exposed above the sea floor.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This technique is extremely useful as it will play an important role in the major sea floor mapping program.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The mapping yields onshore topography as well as underwater elevations.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Sea floor reflectance imaging is another solution product from this system which can benefit mapping of underwater habitats.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This technique has been used for three-dimensional image mapping of California's waters using a hydrographic lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar systems were traditionally able to acquire only a few peak returns, while more recent systems acquire and digitize the entire reflected signal.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Scientists analysed the waveform signal for extracting peak returns using Gaussian decomposition.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Zhuang et al, 2017 used this approach for estimating aboveground biomass.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Handling the huge amounts of full-waveform data is difficult.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Therefore, Gaussian decomposition of the waveforms is effective, since it reduces the data and is supported by existing workflows that support interpretation of 3-D point clouds.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Recent studies investigated voxelisation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The intensities of the waveform samples are inserted into a voxelised space (3-D grayscale image) building up a 3-D representation of the scanned area.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Related metrics and information can then be extracted from that voxelised space.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Structural information can be extracted using 3-D metrics from local areas and there is a case study that used the voxelisation approach for detecting dead standing eucalypt trees in Australia.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Terrestrial applications of lidar (also *terrestrial laser scanning*) happen on the Earth's surface and can be either stationary or mobile.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Stationary terrestrial scanning is most common as a survey method, for example in conventional topography, monitoring, cultural heritage documentation and forensics.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The 3-D point clouds acquired from these types of scanners can be matched with digital images taken of the scanned area from the scanner's location to create realistic looking 3-D models in a relatively short time when compared to other technologies.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Each point in the point cloud is given the colour of the pixel from the image taken at the same location and direction as the laser beam that created the point.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Terrestrial lidar mapping involves a process of occupancy grid map generation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The process involves an array of cells divided into grids which employ a process to store the height values when lidar data falls into the respective grid cell.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] A binary map is then created by applying a particular threshold to the cell values for further processing.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] The next step is to process the radial distance and z-coordinates from each scan to identify which 3-D points correspond to each of the specified grid cell leading to the process of data formation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Mobile lidar (also *mobile laser scanning*) is when two or more scanners are attached to a moving vehicle to collect data along a path.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] These scanners are almost always paired with other kinds of equipment, including GNSS receivers and IMUs.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] One example application is surveying streets, where power lines, exact bridge heights, bordering trees, etc. all need to be taken into account.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] Instead of collecting each of these measurements individually in the field with a tachymeter, a 3-D model from a point cloud can be created where all of the measurements needed can be made, depending on the quality of the data collected.
[src:robotics/lidar-p01] This eliminates the problem of forgetting to take a measurement, so long as the model is available, reliable and has an appropriate level of accuracy.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] There are a wide variety of lidar applications, in addition to the applications listed below, as it is often mentioned in national lidar dataset programs.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Companies are working to cut the cost of lidar sensors, currently anywhere from about US$1,200 to more than $12,000.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lower prices will make lidar more attractive for new markets.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Agricultural robots have been used for a variety of purposes ranging from seed and fertilizer dispersions, sensing techniques as well as crop scouting for the task of weed control.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can help determine where to apply costly fertilizer.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] It can create a topographical map of the fields and reveal slopes and sun exposure of the farmland.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Researchers at the Agricultural Research Service used this topographical data with the farmland yield results from previous years, to categorize land into zones of high, medium, or low yield.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This indicates where to apply fertilizer to maximize yield.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is now used to monitor insects in the field.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The use of lidar can detect the movement and behavior of individual flying insects, with identification down to sex and species.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2017 a patent application was published on this technology in the United States, Europe, and China.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Another application is crop mapping in orchards and vineyards, to detect foliage growth and the need for pruning or other maintenance, detect variations in fruit production, or count plants.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is useful in GNSS-denied situations, such as nut and fruit orchards, where foliage causes interference for agriculture equipment that would otherwise utilize a precise GNSS fix.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors can detect and track the relative position of rows, plants, and other markers so that farming equipment can continue operating until a GNSS fix is reestablished.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Controlling weeds requires identifying plant species.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This can be done by using 3-D lidar and machine learning.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar produces plant contours as a "point cloud" with range and reflectance values.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This data is transformed, and features are extracted from it.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] If the species is known, the features are added as new data.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The species is labelled and its features are initially stored as an example to identify the species in the real environment.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This method is efficient because it uses a low-resolution lidar and supervised learning.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] It includes an easy-to-compute feature set with common statistical features which are independent of the plant size.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In April 2025, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport announced the deployment of a lidar-based platform for real-time monitoring of passenger and vehicle flows.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has many uses in archaeology, including planning of field campaigns, mapping features under forest canopy, and overview of broad, continuous features indistinguishable from the ground.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can produce high-resolution datasets quickly and cheaply.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar-derived products can be easily integrated into a geographic information system (GIS) for analysis and interpretation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can also help to create high-resolution digital elevation models (DEMs) of archaeological sites that can reveal micro-topography that is otherwise hidden by vegetation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The intensity of the returned lidar signal can be used to detect features buried under flat vegetated surfaces such as fields, especially when mapping using the infrared spectrum.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The presence of these features affects plant growth and thus the amount of infrared light reflected back.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] For example, at Fort Beauséjour – Fort Cumberland National Historic Site, Canada, lidar discovered archaeological features related to the siege of the Fort in 1755.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Features that could not be distinguished on the ground or through aerial photography were identified by overlaying hill shades of the DEM created with artificial illumination from various angles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Another example is work at Caracol by Arlen Chase and his wife Diane Zaino Chase.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar was used to search for the legendary city of La Ciudad Blanca or "City of the Monkey God" in the La Mosquitia region of the Honduran jungle.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] During a seven-day mapping period, evidence was found of man-made structures.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In June 2013, the rediscovery of the city of Mahendraparvata was announced.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In southern New England, lidar was used to reveal stone walls, building foundations, abandoned roads, and other landscape features obscured in aerial photography by the region's dense forest canopy.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In Cambodia, lidar data were used by Damian Evans and Roland Fletcher to reveal anthropogenic changes to Angkor landscape.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar revealed that the Purépecha settlement of Angamuco in Michoacán, Mexico had about as many buildings as today's Manhattan; while in 2016, its use in mapping ancient Maya causeways in northern Guatemala, revealed 17 elevated roads linking the ancient city of El Mirador to other sites.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2018, archaeologists using lidar discovered more than 60,000 man-made structures in the Maya Biosphere Reserve, a "major breakthrough" that showed the Maya civilization was much larger than previously thought.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2024, archaeologists using lidar discovered the Upano Valley sites.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Autonomous vehicles may use lidar for obstacle detection and avoidance to navigate safely through environments.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The introduction of lidar was a pivotal occurrence that was the key enabler behind Stanley, the first autonomous vehicle to successfully complete the DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Point cloud output from the lidar sensor provides the necessary data for robot software to determine where potential obstacles exist in the environment and where the robot is in relation to those potential obstacles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Singapore's *Singapore-MIT Alliance for Research and Technology (SMART)* is actively developing technologies for autonomous lidar vehicles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The very first generations of automotive adaptive cruise control systems used only lidar sensors.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In transportation systems, to ensure vehicle and passenger safety and to develop electronic systems that deliver driver assistance, understanding the vehicle and its surrounding environment is essential.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar systems play an important role in the safety of transportation systems.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Many electronic systems which enhance driver assistance and vehicle safety such as adaptive cruise control (ACC), emergency brake assist, and anti-lock braking system (ABS) depend on the detection of a vehicle's environment to act autonomously or semi-autonomously.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar mapping and estimation achieve this.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Current lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors which split the laser beam.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The upper three beams are used for vehicle and obstacles ahead, and the lower beams are used to detect lane markings and road features.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The major advantage of using lidar is that the spatial structure is obtained and this data can be fused with other sensors such as radar, etc. to get a better picture of the vehicle environment in terms of static and dynamic properties of the objects present in the environment.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Conversely, a significant issue with lidar is the difficulty in reconstructing point cloud data in poor weather conditions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In heavy rain, for example, the light pulses emitted from the lidar system are partially reflected off of rain droplets which adds noise to the data, called 'echoes'.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Obstacle detection and road environment recognition using lidar, proposed by Kun Zhou et al. not only focuses on object detection and tracking but also recognizes lane marking and road features.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] As mentioned earlier, the lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors that split the laser beam into six beams.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The upper three layers are used to detect the forward objects such as vehicles and roadside objects.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The sensor is made of weather-resistant material.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The data detected by lidar are clustered to several segments and tracked by Kalman filter.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Data clustering here is done based on characteristics of each segment based on object model, which distinguish different objects such as vehicles, signboards, etc.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] These characteristics include the dimensions of the object, etc.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The reflectors on the rear edges of vehicles are used to differentiate vehicles from other objects.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Object tracking is done using a two-stage Kalman filter considering the stability of tracking and the accelerated motion of objects Lidar reflective intensity data is also used for curb detection by making use of robust regression to deal with occlusions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Road marking is detected using a modified Otsu method by distinguishing rough and shiny surfaces.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Roadside reflectors that indicate lane border are sometimes hidden due to various reasons.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Therefore, other information is needed to recognize the road border.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The lidar used in this method can measure the reflectivity from the object.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Hence, with this data the road border can also be recognized.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Also, the usage of a sensor with a weather-robust head helps to detect the objects even in bad weather conditions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Canopy height model before and after a flood is a good example.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can detect highly detailed canopy height data as well as its road border.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar measurements help identify the spatial structure of the obstacle.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This helps distinguish objects based on size and estimate the impact of driving over it.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar systems provide better range and a large field of view, which helps in detecting obstacles on the curves.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This is one of its major advantages over radar systems, which have a narrower field of view.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The fusion of lidar measurement with different sensors makes the system robust and useful in real-time applications, since lidar-dependent systems cannot estimate the dynamic information about the detected object.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] It has been shown that lidar can be manipulated, such that self-driving cars are tricked into taking evasive action.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has also found many applications for mapping natural and managed landscapes such as forests, wetlands, and grasslands.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Canopy heights, biomass measurements, and leaf area can all be studied using airborne lidar systems.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Similarly, lidar is also used by many industries, including Energy and Railroad, and the Department of Transportation as a faster way of surveying.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Topographic maps can also be generated readily from lidar, including for recreational use such as in the production of orienteering maps.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been applied to estimate and assess the biodiversity of plants, fungi, and animals.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Using southern bull kelp in New Zealand, coastal lidar mapping data has been compared with population genomic evidence to form hypotheses regarding the occurrence and timing of prehistoric earthquake uplift events.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar systems have also been applied to improve forestry management.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Measurements are used to take inventory in forest plots as well as calculate individual tree heights, crown width and crown diameter.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Other statistical analysis use lidar data to estimate total plot information such as canopy volume, mean, minimum and maximum heights, vegetation cover, biomass, and carbon density.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Aerial lidar was used to map the bush fires in Australia in early 2020.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The data was manipulated to view bare earth, and identify healthy and burned vegetation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] High-resolution digital elevation maps generated by airborne and stationary lidar have led to significant advances in geomorphology (the branch of geoscience concerned with the origin and evolution of the Earth surface topography).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2005 the Tour Ronde in the Mont Blanc massif became the first high alpine mountain on which lidar was employed to monitor the increasing occurrence of severe rock-fall over large rock faces allegedly caused by climate change and degradation of permafrost at high altitude.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used in structural geology and geophysics as a combination between airborne lidar and GNSS for the detection and study of faults, for measuring uplift.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The output of the two technologies can produce extremely accurate elevation models for terrain – models that can even measure ground elevation through trees.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This combination was used most famously to find the location of the Seattle Fault in Washington, United States.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This combination also measures uplift at Mount St.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Helens by using data from before and after the 2004 uplift.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar systems monitor glaciers and have the ability to detect subtle amounts of growth or decline.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A satellite-based system, the NASA ICESat, includes a lidar sub-system for this purpose.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The NASA Airborne Topographic Mapper is also used extensively to monitor glaciers and perform coastal change analysis.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The combination is also used by soil scientists while creating a soil survey.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The detailed terrain modeling allows soil scientists to see slope changes and landform breaks which indicate patterns in soil spatial relationships.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Initially, based on ruby lasers, lidar for meteorological applications was constructed shortly after the invention of the laser and represents one of the first applications of laser technology.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar technology has since expanded vastly in capability and lidar systems are used to perform a range of measurements that include profiling clouds, measuring winds, studying aerosols, and quantifying various atmospheric components.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Atmospheric components can in turn provide useful information including surface pressure (by measuring the absorption of oxygen or nitrogen), greenhouse gas emissions (carbon dioxide and methane), photosynthesis (carbon dioxide), fires (carbon monoxide), and humidity (water vapor).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Atmospheric lidars can be either ground-based, airborne or satellite-based depending on the type of measurement.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] 2. by measuring the scattered reflection off the ground (when the lidar is airborne) or other hard surface.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Backscatter from the atmosphere directly gives a measure of clouds and aerosols.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Other derived measurements from backscatter such as winds or cirrus ice crystals require careful selecting of the wavelength and/or polarization detected.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] *Doppler lidar* and *Rayleigh Doppler lidar* are used to measure temperature and wind speed along the beam by measuring the frequency of the backscattered light.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The Doppler broadening of gases in motion allows the determination of properties via the resulting frequency shift.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Scanning lidars, such as NASA's conical-scanning HARLIE, have been used to measure atmospheric wind velocity.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The ESA wind mission *ADM-Aeolus* will be equipped with a Doppler lidar system in order to provide global measurements of vertical wind profiles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A doppler lidar system was used in the 2008 Summer Olympics to measure wind fields during the yacht competition.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Doppler lidar systems are also now beginning to be successfully applied in the renewable energy sector to acquire wind speed, turbulence, wind veer, and wind shear data.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Both pulsed and continuous wave systems are being used.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Pulsed systems use signal timing to obtain vertical distance resolution, whereas continuous wave systems rely on detector focusing.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The term *eolics* has been proposed to describe the collaborative and interdisciplinary study of wind using computational fluid mechanics simulations and Doppler lidar measurements.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The ground reflection of an airborne lidar gives a measure of surface reflectivity (assuming the atmospheric transmittance is well known) at the lidar wavelength, however, the ground reflection is typically used for making absorption measurements of the atmosphere.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] "Differential absorption lidar" (DIAL) measurements utilize two or more closely spaced (less than 1 nm) wavelengths to factor out surface reflectivity as well as other transmission losses, since these factors are relatively insensitive to wavelength.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] When tuned to the appropriate absorption lines of a particular gas, DIAL measurements can be used to determine the concentration (mixing ratio) of that particular gas in the atmosphere.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This is referred to as an *integrated path differential absorption* (IPDA) approach, since it is a measure of the integrated absorption along the entire lidar path.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars can be either pulsed or CW and typically use two or more wavelengths.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars have been used for remote sensing of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In Japan, differential absorption lidar (DIAL) and Raman lidar technologies are being developed to improve the accuracy of flood forecasting and rainfall prediction.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A research by several companies, universities, and institutes, led by Kyushu University is conducting work on meteorological sensing and flood-risk modelling under a government program.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In May 2025, EKO Instruments began a field study on Goto Fukue Island, Nagasaki Prefecture, using a Micropulse DIAL lidar system provided by the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NSF NCAR).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The study compares DIAL performance with existing Raman lidar systems.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Ltd. signed a technology license agreement in February 2025 with Montana State University, NSF NCAR, and NASA, covering key DIAL-related patents.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Few military applications are known to be in place and are classified (such as the lidar-based speed measurement of the AGM-129 ACM stealth nuclear cruise missile), but a considerable amount of research is underway in their use for imaging.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Higher resolution systems collect enough detail to identify targets, such as tanks.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Examples of military applications of lidar include the Airborne Laser Mine Detection System (ALMDS) for counter-mine warfare by Areté Associates.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A NATO report (RTO-TR-SET-098) evaluated the potential technologies to do stand-off detection for the discrimination of biological warfare agents.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The potential technologies evaluated were long-wave infrared (LWIR), differential scattering (DISC), and ultraviolet laser-induced fluorescence (UV-LIF).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Short-range compact spectrometric lidar based on laser-induced fluorescence (LIF) would address the presence of bio-threats in aerosol form over critical indoor, semi-enclosed and outdoor venues such as stadiums, subways, and airports.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This near real-time capability would enable rapid detection of a bioaerosol release and allow for timely implementation of measures to protect occupants and minimize the extent of contamination.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The Long-Range Biological Standoff Detection System (LR-BSDS) was developed for the U.S.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Army to provide the earliest possible standoff warning of a biological attack.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] It is an airborne system carried by helicopter to detect synthetic aerosol clouds containing biological and chemical agents at long range.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The LR-BSDS, with a detection range of 30 km or more, was fielded in June 1997.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Five lidar units produced by the German company Sick AG were used for short range detection on Stanley, the autonomous car that won the 2005 DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A robotic Boeing AH-6 performed a fully autonomous flight in June 2010, including avoiding obstacles using lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The calculation of ore volumes is accomplished by periodic (monthly) scanning in areas of ore removal, then comparing surface data to the previous scan.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors may also be used for obstacle detection and avoidance for robotic mining vehicles such as in the Komatsu Autonomous Haulage System (AHS) used in Rio Tinto's Mine of the Future.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A worldwide network of observatories uses lidars to measure the distance to reflectors placed on the Moon, allowing the position of the Moon to be measured with millimeter precision and tests of general relativity to be done.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] MOLA, the Mars Orbiting Laser Altimeter, used a lidar instrument in a Mars-orbiting satellite (the NASA Mars Global Surveyor) to produce a spectacularly precise global topographic survey of the red planet.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Laser altimeters produced global elevation models of Mars, the Moon (Lunar Orbiter Laser Altimeter (LOLA)), and Mercury (Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA), NEAR–Shoemaker Laser Rangefinder (NLR)).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Future missions will also include laser altimeter experiments such as the Ganymede Laser Altimeter (GALA) as part of the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In September, 2008, the NASA *Phoenix* lander used lidar to detect snow in the atmosphere of Mars.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In atmospheric physics, lidar is used as a remote detection instrument to measure densities of certain constituents of the middle and upper atmosphere, such as potassium, sodium, or molecular nitrogen and oxygen.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] These measurements can be used to calculate temperatures.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to measure wind speed and to provide information about vertical distribution of the aerosol particles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] At the JET nuclear fusion research facility in the UK near Abingdon, Oxfordshire, lidar Thomson scattering is used to determine electron density and temperature profiles of the plasma.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has been widely used in rock mechanics for rock mass characterization and slope change detection.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Some important geomechanical properties from the rock mass can be extracted from the 3-D point clouds obtained by means of the lidar.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Some of these properties have been used to assess the geomechanical quality of the rock mass through the RMR index.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Moreover, as the orientations of discontinuities can be extracted using the existing methodologies, it is possible to assess the geomechanical quality of a rock slope through the SMR index.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In addition to this, the comparison of different 3-D point clouds from a slope acquired at different times allows researchers to study the changes produced on the scene during this time interval as a result of rockfalls or any other landsliding processes.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] THOR is a laser designed toward measuring Earth's atmospheric conditions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The laser enters a cloud cover and measures the thickness of the return halo.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The sensor has a fiber optic aperture with a width of 7+1⁄2 inches (19 cm) that is used to measure the return light.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar technology is being used in robotics for the perception of the environment as well as object classification.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The ability of lidar technology to provide three-dimensional elevation maps of the terrain, high precision distance to the ground, and approach velocity can enable safe landing of robotic and crewed vehicles with a high degree of precision.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is also widely used in robotics for simultaneous localization and mapping and is well-integrated into robot simulators.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Refer to the Military section above for further examples.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is increasingly being utilized for rangefinding and orbital element calculation of relative velocity in proximity operations and stationkeeping of spacecraft.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been used for atmospheric studies from space.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Short pulses of laser light beamed from a spacecraft can reflect off tiny particles in the atmosphere and back to a telescope aligned with the spacecraft laser.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] By precisely timing the lidar echo, and by measuring how much laser light is received by the telescope, scientists can accurately determine the location, distribution and nature of the particles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The result is a revolutionary new tool for studying constituents in the atmosphere, from cloud droplets to industrial pollutants, which are difficult to detect by other means.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Laser altimetry is used to make digital elevation maps of planets, including the Mars Orbital Laser Altimeter (MOLA) mapping of Mars, the Lunar Orbital Laser Altimeter (LOLA) and Lunar Altimeter (LALT) mapping of the Moon, and the Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA) mapping of Mercury.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] It is also used to help navigate the helicopter *Ingenuity* in its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar sensors are used by companies in the remote sensing field.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] They can be used to create a DTM (digital terrain model) or DEM (digital elevation model); this is quite a common practice for larger areas as a plane can acquire 3–4 km (2–2+1⁄2 mi) wide swaths in a single flyover.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Greater vertical accuracy of below 50 mm (2 in) can be achieved with a lower flyover, even in forests, where it is able to give the height of the canopy as well as the ground elevation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Typically, a GNSS receiver configured over a georeferenced control point is needed to link the data in with the WGS (World Geodetic System).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is also in use in hydrographic surveying.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Depending upon the clarity of the water lidar can measure depths from 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft) with a vertical accuracy of 15 cm (6 in) and horizontal accuracy of 2.5 m (8 ft).
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in the railroad industry to generate asset health reports for asset management and by departments of transportation to assess their road conditions.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] CivilMaps.com is a leading company in the field.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in adaptive cruise control (ACC) systems for automobiles.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Systems such as those by Siemens, Hella, Ouster and Cepton use a lidar device mounted on the front of the vehicle, such as the bumper, to monitor the distance between the vehicle and any vehicle in front of it.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In the event where the vehicle in front slows down or is too close, the ACC applies the brakes to slow the vehicle.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] When the road ahead is clear, the ACC allows the vehicle to accelerate to a speed preset by the driver.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A lidar-based device, the Ceilometer, is used at airports worldwide to measure the height of clouds on runway approach paths.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can be used to increase the energy output from wind farms by accurately measuring wind speeds and wind turbulence.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Experimental lidar systems can be mounted on the nacelle of a wind turbine or integrated into the rotating spinner to measure oncoming horizontal winds, winds in the wake of the wind turbine, and proactively adjust blades to protect components and increase power.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used to characterise the incident wind resource for comparison with wind turbine power production to verify the performance of the wind turbine by measuring the wind turbine's power curve.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Wind farm optimization can be considered a topic in *applied eolics*.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Another aspect of lidar in wind related industry is to use computational fluid dynamics over lidar-scanned surfaces in order to assess the wind potential, which can be used for optimal wind farm placement.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to assist planners and developers in optimizing solar photovoltaic systems at the city level by determining appropriate roof tops and for determining shading losses.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Recent airborne laser scanning efforts have focused on ways to estimate the amount of solar light hitting vertical building facades, or by incorporating more detailed shading losses by considering the influence from vegetation and larger surrounding terrain.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The 2017 exploration game *Scanner Sombre*, by Introversion Software, uses lidar as a fundamental game mechanic.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In *Build the Earth*, lidar is used to create accurate renders of terrain in *Minecraft* to account for any errors (mainly regarding elevation) in the default generation.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The process of rendering terrain into Build the Earth is limited by the amount of data available in region as well as the speed it takes to convert the file into block data.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Lidar technology enhances physical security by providing precise, privacy-compliant threat detection for applications such as perimeter protection, building facades, and critical infrastructure monitoring.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] These systems utilize laser-based sensors to create high-density point clouds that function reliably in challenging environmental conditions, including rain, snow, and complete darkness.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] A key advantage of modern systems is the use of 3D lidar, which creates precise volumetric detection zones capturing height, width, and depth, allowing for the accurate classification of object size and movement speed.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The video for the 2007 song "House of Cards" by Radiohead was believed to be the first use of real-time 3-D laser scanning to record a music video.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The range data in the video is not completely from a lidar, as structured light scanning is also used.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2020, Apple introduced the fourth generation of iPad Pro with a lidar sensor integrated into the rear camera module, especially developed for augmented reality (AR) experiences.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The feature was later included in the iPhone 12 Pro lineup and subsequent Pro models.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] On Apple devices, lidar empowers portrait mode pictures with night mode, quickens auto focus and improves accuracy in the Measure app.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In 2022, *Wheel of Fortune* started using lidar technology to track when Vanna White moves her hand over the puzzle board to reveal letters.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The first episode to have this technology was in the season 40 premiere.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In flash lidar, the entire field of view is illuminated with a wide diverging laser beam in a single pulse.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This is in contrast to conventional scanning lidar, which uses a collimated laser beam that illuminates a single point at a time, and the beam is raster scanned to illuminate the field of view point-by-point.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] This illumination method requires a different detection scheme as well.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In both scanning and flash lidar, a time-of-flight camera is used to collect information about both the 3-D location and intensity of the light incident on it in every frame.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] However, in scanning lidar, this camera contains only a point sensor, while in flash lidar, the camera contains either a 1-D or a 2-D sensor array, each pixel of which collects 3-D location and intensity information.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] In both cases, the depth information is collected using the time of flight of the laser pulse (i.e., the time it takes each laser pulse to hit the target and return to the sensor), which requires the pulsing of the laser and acquisition by the camera to be synchronized.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The result is a camera that takes pictures of distance, instead of colors.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Flash lidar is especially advantageous when compared to scanning lidar, when the camera, scene, or both are moving, since the entire scene is illuminated at the same time.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] With scanning lidar, motion can cause "jitter" from the lapse in time as the laser rasters over the scene.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] As with all forms of lidar, the onboard source of illumination makes flash lidar an active sensor.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The signal that is returned is processed by embedded algorithms to produce a nearly instantaneous 3-D rendering of objects and terrain features within the field of view of the sensor.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The laser pulse repetition frequency is sufficient for generating 3-D videos with high resolution and accuracy.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The high frame rate of the sensor makes it a useful tool for a variety of applications that benefit from real-time visualization, such as highly precise remote landing operations.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] By immediately returning a 3-D elevation mesh of target landscapes, a flash sensor can be used to identify optimal landing zones in autonomous spacecraft landing scenarios.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Seeing at a distance requires a powerful burst of light.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] The power is limited to levels that do not damage human retinas.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] However, low-cost silicon imagers do not read light in the eye-safe spectrum.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Instead, gallium-arsenide imagers are required, which can boost costs to $200,000.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Gallium-arsenide is the same compound used to produce high-cost, high-efficiency solar panels usually used in space applications.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] Computer stereo vision has shown promise as an alternative to lidar for close-range applications.
[src:robotics/lidar-p02] It is significantly more cost effective when appropriate.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] For example, consider navigating a mobile robot inside a building to a distant waypoint.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] It should execute this task while avoiding walls and not falling down stairs.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A motion planning algorithm would take a description of these tasks as input, and produce the speed and turning commands sent to the robot's wheels.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Motion planning algorithms might address robots with a larger number of joints (e.g., industrial manipulators), more complex tasks (e.g. manipulation of objects), different constraints (e.g., a car that can only drive forward), and uncertainty (e.g. imperfect models of the environment or robot).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Motion planning has several robotics applications, such as autonomy, automation, and robot design in CAD software, as well as applications in other fields, such as animating digital characters, video game, architectural design, robotic surgery, and the study of biological molecules.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A basic motion planning problem is to compute a continuous path that connects a start configuration S and a goal configuration G, while avoiding collision with known obstacles.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The robot and obstacle geometry is described in a 2D or 3D *workspace*, while the motion is represented as a path in (possibly higher-dimensional) configuration space.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A configuration describes the pose of the robot, and the configuration space C is the set of all possible configurations.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The set of configurations that avoids collision with obstacles is called the free space Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The complement of Cfree in C is called the obstacle or forbidden region.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Often, it is prohibitively difficult to explicitly compute the shape of Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] However, testing whether a given configuration is in Cfree is efficient.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] First, forward kinematics determine the position of the robot's geometry, and collision detection tests if the robot's geometry collides with the environment's geometry.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Target space is a subspace of free space which denotes where we want the robot to move to.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] In global motion planning, target space is observable by the robot's sensors.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] However, in local motion planning, the robot cannot observe the target space in some states.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] To solve this problem, the robot goes through several virtual target spaces, each of which is located within the observable area (around the robot).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A virtual target space is called a sub-goal.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Obstacle space is a space that the robot can not move to.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Obstacle space is not opposite of free space.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Low-dimensional problems can be solved with grid-based algorithms that overlay a grid on top of configuration space, or geometric algorithms that compute the shape and connectivity of Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Exact motion planning for high-dimensional systems under complex constraints is computationally intractable.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Potential-field algorithms are efficient, but fall prey to local minima (an exception is the harmonic potential fields).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms avoid the problem of local minima, and solve many problems quite quickly.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] They are unable to determine that no path exists, but they have a probability of failure that decreases to zero as more time is spent.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms are currently considered state-of-the-art for motion planning in high-dimensional spaces, and have been applied to problems which have dozens or even hundreds of dimensions (robotic manipulators, biological molecules, animated digital characters, and legged robots).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches overlay a grid on configuration space and assume each configuration is identified with a grid point.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] At each grid point, the robot is allowed to move to adjacent grid points as long as the line between them is completely contained within Cfree (this is tested with collision detection).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] This discretizes the set of actions, and search algorithms (like A*) are used to find a path from the start to the goal.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] These approaches require setting a grid resolution.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Search is faster with coarser grids, but the algorithm will fail to find paths through narrow portions of Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Furthermore, the number of points on the grid grows exponentially in the configuration space dimension, which make them inappropriate for high-dimensional problems.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Traditional grid-based approaches produce paths whose heading changes are constrained to multiples of a given base angle, often resulting in suboptimal paths.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Any-angle path planning approaches find shorter paths by propagating information along grid edges (to search fast) without constraining their paths to grid edges (to find short paths).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches often need to search repeatedly, for example, when the knowledge of the robot about the configuration space changes or the configuration space itself changes during path following.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Incremental heuristic search algorithms replan fast by using experience with the previous similar path-planning problems to speed up their search for the current one.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] These approaches are similar to grid-based search approaches except that they generate a paving covering entirely the configuration space instead of a grid.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The paving is decomposed into two subpavings X−,X+ made with boxes such that X− ⊂ Cfree ⊂ X+.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Characterizing Cfree amounts to solve a set inversion problem.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Interval analysis could thus be used when Cfree cannot be described by linear inequalities in order to have a guaranteed enclosure.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The robot is thus allowed to move freely in X−, and cannot go outside X+.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] To both subpavings, a neighbor graph is built and paths can be found using algorithms such as Dijkstra or A*.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] When a path is feasible in X−, it is also feasible in Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] When no path exists in X+ from one initial configuration to the goal, we have the guarantee that no feasible path exists in Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] As for the grid-based approach, the interval approach is inappropriate for high-dimensional problems, due to the fact that the number of boxes to be generated grows exponentially with respect to the dimension of configuration space.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] An illustration is provided by the three figures on the right where a hook with two degrees of freedom has to move from the left to the right, avoiding two horizontal small segments.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Nicolas Delanoue has shown that the decomposition with subpavings using interval analysis also makes it possible to characterize the topology of Cfree such as counting its number of connected components.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Given a bundle of rays around the current position attributed with their length hitting a wall, the robot moves into the direction of the longest ray unless a door is identified.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Such an algorithm was used for modeling emergency egress from buildings.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] One approach is to treat the robot's configuration as a point in a potential field that combines attraction to the goal, and repulsion from obstacles.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The resulting trajectory is output as the path.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] This approach has advantages in that the trajectory is produced with little computation.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] However, they can become trapped in local minima of the potential field and fail to find a path, or can find a non-optimal path.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The artificial potential fields can be treated as continuum equations similar to electrostatic potential fields (treating the robot like a point charge), or motion through the field can be discretized using a set of linguistic rules.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A navigation function or a probabilistic navigation function are sorts of artificial potential functions which have the quality of not having minimum points except the target point.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A basic algorithm samples N configurations in C, and retains those in Cfree to use as *milestones*.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A roadmap is then constructed that connects two milestones P and Q if the line segment PQ is completely in Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Again, collision detection is used to test inclusion in Cfree.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] To find a path that connects S and G, they are added to the roadmap.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] If a path in the roadmap links S and G, the planner succeeds, and returns that path.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] If not, the reason is not definitive: either there is no path in Cfree, or the planner did not sample enough milestones.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] These algorithms work well for high-dimensional configuration spaces, because unlike combinatorial algorithms, their running time is not (explicitly) exponentially dependent on the dimension of C.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] They are also (generally) substantially easier to implement.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] They are probabilistically complete, meaning the probability that they will produce a solution approaches 1 as more time is spent.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] However, they cannot determine if no solution exists.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Given basic *visibility* conditions on Cfree, it has been proven that as the number of configurations N grows higher, the probability that the above algorithm finds a solution approaches 1 exponentially.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Visibility is not explicitly dependent on the dimension of C; it is possible to have a high-dimensional space with "good" visibility or a low-dimensional space with "poor" visibility.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The experimental success of sample-based methods suggests that most commonly seen spaces have good visibility.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] A motion planner is said to be *complete* if the planner in finite time either produces a solution or correctly reports that there is none.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Most complete algorithms are geometry-based.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The performance of a complete planner is assessed by its computational complexity.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] When proving this property mathematically, one has to make sure, that it happens in finite time and not just in the asymptotic limit.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] This is especially problematic, if there occur infinite sequences (that converge only in the limiting case) during a specific proving technique, since then, theoretically, the algorithm will never stop.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Intuitive "tricks" (often based on induction) are typically mistakenly thought to converge, which they do only for the infinite limit.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] In other words, the solution exists, but the planner will never report it.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] This property therefore is related to Turing completeness and serves in most cases as a theoretical underpinning/guidance.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Planners based on a brute force approach are always complete, but are only realizable for finite and discrete setups.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] In practice, the termination of the algorithm can always be guaranteed by using a counter, that allows only for a maximum number of iterations and then always stops with or without solution.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] For realtime systems, this is typically achieved by using a watchdog timer, that will simply kill the process.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The watchdog has to be independent of all processes (typically realized by low level interrupt routines).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The asymptotic case described in the previous paragraph, however, will not be reached in this way.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] It will report the best one it has found so far (which is better than nothing) or none, but cannot correctly report that there is none.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] All realizations including a watchdog are always incomplete (except all cases can be evaluated in finite time).
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Completeness can only be provided by a very rigorous mathematical correctness proof (often aided by tools and graph based methods) and should only be done by specialized experts if the application includes safety content.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] On the other hand, disproving completeness is easy, since one just needs to find one infinite loop or one wrong result returned.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Formal Verification/Correctness of algorithms is a research field on its own.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] The correct setup of these test cases is a highly sophisticated task.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Many algorithms have been developed to handle variants of this basic problem.
[src:robotics/motion-planning] Hybrid systems are those that mix discrete and continuous behavior.
[src:robotics/odometry] The word *odometry* is composed of the Greek words *odos* (meaning "route") and *metron* (meaning "measure").
[src:robotics/odometry] Suppose a robot has rotary encoders on its wheels or on its legged joints.
[src:robotics/odometry] It drives forward for some time and then would like to know how far it has traveled.
[src:robotics/odometry] It can measure how far the wheels have rotated, and if it knows the circumference of its wheels, compute the distance.
[src:robotics/odometry] Train operations are also frequent users of odometrics.
[src:robotics/odometry] Typically, a train gets an absolute position by passing over stationary sensors in the tracks, while odometry is used to calculate relative position while the train is between the sensors.
[src:robotics/odometry] Suppose a simple robot has two wheels, both capable of moving forward or in reverse, positioned parallel to each other and equidistant from the robot's center.
[src:robotics/odometry] Additionally, each motor has a rotary encoder, allowing determination of whether either wheel has traveled one "unit" forward or reverse along the floor.
[src:robotics/odometry] This unit is defined as the ratio of the wheel's circumference to the encoder's resolution.
[src:robotics/odometry] If the left wheel were to move forward one unit while the right wheel remained stationary, then the right wheel acts as a pivot, and the left wheel traces a circular arc in the clockwise direction.
[src:robotics/odometry] Since one's unit of distance is usually tiny, one can approximate by assuming that this arc is a line.
[src:robotics/odometry] Thus, the original position of the left wheel, the final position of the left wheel, and the position of the right wheel form a triangle, which one can call *A*.
[src:robotics/odometry] Also, the original position of the center, the final position of the center, and the position of the right wheel form a triangle which one can call *B*.
[src:robotics/odometry] Since the center of the robot is equidistant to either wheel, and as they share the angle formed at the right wheel, triangles *A* and *B* are similar triangles.
[src:robotics/odometry] In this situation, the magnitude of the change of position of the center of the robot is one half of a unit.
[src:robotics/odometry] The angle of this change can be determined using the law of sines.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] An **end effector** or **tool head** is the device at the end of a robotic arm, designed to interact with the environment.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The exact nature of this device depends on the application of the robot.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] In the strict definition, which originates from serial robotic manipulators, the end effector means the last link (or end) of the robot.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] At this endpoint, the tools are attached.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] In a wider sense, an end effector can be seen as the part of a robot that interacts with the work environment.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] This does not refer to the wheels of a mobile robot or the feet of a humanoid robot, which are not end effectors but rather part of a robot's mobility.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] End effectors may consist of a gripper or a tool.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Ingressive: pins, needles or hackles which physically penetrate the surface of the object (used in textile, carbon, and glass fiber handling).
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Astrictive: attractive forces applied to the object's surface (whether by vacuum, magneto-, or electroadhesion).
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Contigutive: requiring direct contact for adhesion to take place (such as glue, surface tension, or freezing).
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] These categories describe the physical effects used to achieve a stable grasp between a gripper and the object to be grasped.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Industrial grippers may employ mechanical, suction, or magnetic means.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Vacuum cups and electromagnets dominate the automotive field and metal sheet handling.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Bernoulli grippers exploit the airflow between the gripper and the part, in which a lifting force brings the gripper and part close each other (using Bernoulli's principle).
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Bernoulli grippers are a type of contactless grippers; the object remains confined in the force field generated by the gripper without coming into direct contact with it.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Bernoulli grippers have been adopted in photovoltaic cell handling, silicon wafer handling, and in the textile and leather industries.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Other principles are less used at the macro scale (part size >5mm), but in the last ten years, have demonstrated interesting applications in micro-handling.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Electrostatic grippers use a charge-difference between gripper and part (electrostatic force) often activated by the gripper itself, while van der Waals grippers are based on the low force (still electrostatic) of atomic attraction between the molecules of the gripper and those of the object.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Capillary grippers use the surface tension of a liquid meniscus between the gripper and the part to center, align and grasp a part.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Cryogenic grippers freeze a small amount of liquid, with the resulting ice supplying the necessary force to lift and handle the object (this principle is used also in food handling and in textile grasping).
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Laser grippers are known also as laser tweezers.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] A particular category of friction/jaw grippers is that of needle grippers.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] These are called intrusive grippers, exploiting both friction and form-closure as standard mechanical grippers.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The most known mechanical gripper can be of two, three or even five fingers.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] A common form of robotic grasping is force closure.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Generally, the gripping mechanism is done by the grippers or mechanical fingers.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Two-finger grippers tend to be used for industrial robots performing specific tasks in less-complex applications.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Two types of mechanisms used in two-finger gripping account for the shape of the surface to be gripped, and the force required to grip the object.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The shape of the fingers' gripping surface can be chosen according to the shape of the objects to be manipulated.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] For example, if a robot is designed to lift a round object, the gripper surface shape can be a concave impression of it to make the grip efficient.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] For a square shape, the surface can be a plane.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Though there are numerous forces acting over the body that has been lifted by a robotic arm, the main force is the frictional force.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The gripping surface can be made of a soft material with high coefficient of friction so that the surface of the object is not damaged.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The robotic gripper must withstand not only the weight of the object but also acceleration and the motion that is caused by frequent movement of the object.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] A more complete equation would account for the direction of movement.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] For example, when the body is moved upwards, against gravitational force, the force required will be more than that towards the gravitational force.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Here, the value of $\,g$ should be taken as the acceleration due to gravity and $\,a$ the acceleration due to movement.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] For many physically interactive manipulation tasks, such as writing and handling a screwdriver, a task-related grasp criterion can be applied in order to choose grasps that are most appropriate to meeting specific task requirements.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Several task-oriented grasp quality metrics were proposed to guide the selection of a good grasp that would satisfy the task requirements.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The end effectors that can be used as tools serve various purposes, including spot-welding in an assembly, spray-painting where uniformity of painting is necessary, and other purposes where the working conditions are dangerous for human beings.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Surgical robots have end effectors that are specifically manufactured for the purpose.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The end effector of an assembly-line robot would typically be a welding head, or a paint spray gun.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] A surgical robot's end effector could be a scalpel or other tool used in surgery.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] Other possible end effectors might be machine tools such as a drill or milling cutters.
[src:robotics/robot-end-effector] The end effector on the space shuttle's robotic arm uses a pattern of wires which close like the aperture of a camera around a handle or other grasping point.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Despite the importance of reactivity and low latency in robot control, ROS is not a real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] However, it is possible to integrate ROS with real-time computing code.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The lack of support for real-time systems has been addressed in the creation of ROS 2, a major revision of the ROS API which will take advantage of modern libraries and technologies for core ROS functions and add support for real-time code and embedded system hardware.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Both the language-independent tools and the main client libraries (C++, Python, and Lisp) are released under the terms of the BSD license, and as such are open-source software and free for both commercial and research use.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The majority of other packages are licensed under a variety of open-source licenses.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] These other packages implement commonly used functionality and applications such as hardware drivers, robot models, datatypes, planning, perception, simultaneous localization and mapping (SLAM), simulation tools, and other algorithms.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The main ROS client libraries are geared toward a Unix-like system, mostly because of their dependence on large sets of open-source software dependencies.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] For these client libraries, Ubuntu Linux is listed as "Supported" while other variants such as Fedora Linux, macOS, and Microsoft Windows are designated "experimental" and are supported by the community.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] A JavaScript client library, roslibjs has also been developed which enables integration of software into a ROS system via any standards-compliant web browser.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Sometime before 2007, the first pieces of what eventually would become ROS began coalescing at Stanford University.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Eric Berger and Keenan Wyrobek, PhD students working in Kenneth Salisbury's The Robotics laboratory at Stanford, was leading the Personal Robotics Program.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In an attempt to remedy this situation, the two students set out to make a baseline system that would provide a starting place for others in academia to build upon.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In the words of Eric Berger, "something that didn’t suck, in all of those different dimensions".
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Early funding of US$50,000 was provided by Joanna Hoffman and Alain Rossmann, which supported the development of the PR1.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] While seeking funding for further development, Eric Berger and Keenan Wyrobek met Scott Hassan, the founder of Willow Garage, a technology incubator which was working on an autonomous SUV and a solar autonomous boat.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Hassan shared Berger and Wyrobek's vision of a "Linux for robotics", and invited them to come and work at Willow Garage.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Willow Garage was started in January 2007, and the first commit of ROS code was made to SourceForge on 7 November 2007.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Willow Garage began developing the PR2 robot as a follow-up to the PR1, and ROS as the software to run it.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Groups from more than twenty institutions made contributions to ROS, both the core software and the growing number of packages that worked with ROS to form a greater software ecosystem.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] That people outside of Willow were contributing to ROS (especially from Stanford's STAIR project) meant that ROS was a multi-robot platform from the start.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In December 2008, Willow Garage met the first of its three internal milestones: continuous navigation for the PR2 over two days and a distance of pi kilometers.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Soon after, an early version of ROS (0.4 Mango Tango) was released, followed by the first RVIZ documentation and the first paper on ROS.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In early summer, the second internal milestone: having the PR2 navigate the office, open doors, and plug itself it in, was reached.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] This was followed in August by the initiation of the ROS.org website.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Early tutorials on ROS were posted in December, preparing for the release of ROS 1.0, in January 2010.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] This was Milestone 3: producing tons of documentation and tutorials for the enormous abilities that Willow Garage's engineers had developed over the preceding 3 years.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Following this, Willow Garage achieved one of its longest-held goals: giving away 10 PR2 robots to worthy academic institutions.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] This had long been a goal of the founders, as they felt that the PR2 could kick-start robotics research around the world.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] This, combined with Willow Garage's highly successful internship program (run from 2008 to 2010 by Melonee Wise), helped to spread the word about ROS throughout the robotics world.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The first official ROS distribution release: ROS Box Turtle, was released on 2 March 2010, marking the first time that ROS was officially distributed with a set of versioned packages for public use.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] These developments led to the first drone running ROS, the first autonomous car running ROS, and the adaption of ROS for Lego Mindstorms.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] With the PR2 Beta program well underway, the PR2 robot was officially released for commercial purchase on 9 September 2010.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] 2011 was a banner year for ROS with the launch of ROS Answers, a Q/A forum for ROS users, on 15 February; the introduction of the highly successful TurtleBot robot kit on 18 April; and the total number of ROS repositories passing 100 on 5 May.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Willow Garage began 2012 by creating the Open Source Robotics Foundation (OSRF) in April.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The OSRF was immediately awarded a software contract by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA).
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Later that year, the first ROSCon was held in St.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Paul, Minnesota, the first book on ROS, *ROS By Example*, was published, and Baxter, the first commercial robot to run ROS, was announced by Rethink Robotics.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Soon after passing its fifth anniversary in November, ROS began running on every continent on 3 December 2012.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In February 2013, the OSRF became the primary software maintainers for ROS, foreshadowing the announcement in August that Willow Garage would be absorbed by its founders, Suitable Technologies.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] At this point, ROS had released seven major versions (up to ROS Groovy), and had users all over the globe.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] This chapter of ROS development would be finalized when Clearpath Robotics took over support responsibilities for PR2 in early 2014.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In the years since OSRF took over the primary development of ROS, a new version has been released every year, while interest in ROS continues to grow.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROSCons have occurred every year since 2012, co-located with either ICRA or IROS, two flagship robotics conferences.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Meetups of ROS developers have been organized in a variety of countries, a number of ROS books have been published, and many educational programs initiated.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] On 1 September 2014, NASA announced the first robot to run ROS in space: Robotnaut 2, on the International Space Station.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In 2017, the OSRF changed its name to Open Robotics.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Tech giants Amazon and Microsoft began to take an interest in ROS during this time, with Microsoft porting core ROS to Windows in September 2018, followed by Amazon Web Services releasing RoboMaker in November 2018.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS 2 was announced at ROSCon 2014, the first commits to the ros2 repository were made in February 2015, followed by alpha releases in August 2015.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The first distribution release of ROS 2, Ardent Apalone, was released on 8 December 2017, ushering in a new era of next-generation ROS development.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS was designed to be open source, intending that users would be able to choose the configuration of tools and libraries that interacted with the core of ROS so that users could shift their software stacks to fit their robot and application area.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] As such, there is very little which is core to ROS, beyond the general structure within which programs must exist and communicate.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In one sense, ROS is the underlying plumbing behind nodes and message passing.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] However, in reality, ROS is not only plumbing, but a rich and mature set of tools, a wide-ranging set of robot-agnostic abilities provided by packages, and a greater ecosystem of additions to ROS.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS processes are represented as nodes in a graph structure, connected by edges called topics.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS nodes can pass messages to one another through topics, make service calls to other nodes, provide a service for other nodes, or set or retrieve shared data from a communal database called the parameter server.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] A process called the ROS1 Master makes all of this possible by registering nodes to themselves, setting up node-to-node communication for topics, and controlling parameter server updates.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Messages and service calls do not pass through the master, rather the master sets up peer-to-peer communication between all node processes after they register themselves with the master.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] This decentralized architecture lends itself well to robots, which often consist of a subset of networked computer hardware, and may communicate with off-board computers for heavy computing or commands.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] A node represents one process running the ROS graph.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Every node has a name, which registers with the ROS1 master before it can take any other actions.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Multiple nodes with different names can exist under different namespaces, or a node can be defined as anonymous, in which case it will randomly generate an additional identifier to add to its given name.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Nodes are at the center of ROS programming, as most ROS client code is in the form of a ROS node which takes actions based on information received from other nodes, sends information to other nodes, or sends and receives requests for actions to and from other nodes.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Topics are named buses over which nodes send and receive messages.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Topic names must be unique within their namespace as well.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] To send messages to a topic, a node must publish to said topic, while to receive messages it must subscribe.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The publish/subscribe model is anonymous: no node knows which nodes are sending or receiving on a topic, only that it is sending/receiving on that topic.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The types of messages passed on a topic vary widely and can be user-defined.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The content of these messages can be sensor data, motor control commands, state information, actuator commands, or anything else.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] A service represents an action that a node can take which will have a single result.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] As such, services are often used for actions that have a defined start and end, such as capturing a one-frame image, rather than processing velocity commands to a wheel motor or odometer data from a wheel encoder.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Nodes advertise services and call services from one another.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The parameter server is a database shared between nodes which allows for communal access to static or semi-static information.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Data that does not change frequently and as such will be infrequently accessed, such as the distance between two fixed points in the environment, or the weight of the robot, are good candidates for storage in the parameter server.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS's core functionality is augmented by a variety of tools that allow developers to visualize and record data, easily navigate the ROS package structures, and create scripts automating complex configuration and setup processes.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The addition of these tools greatly increases the abilities of systems using ROS by simplifying and providing solutions to several common robotics development problems.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] These tools are provided in packages like any other algorithm, but rather than providing implementations of hardware drivers or algorithms for various robotic tasks, these packages provide task and robot-agnostic tools that come with the core of most modern ROS installations.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] rviz (Robot Visualization tool) is a three-dimensional visualizer used to visualize robots, the environments they work in, and sensor data.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] It is a highly configurable tool, with many different types of visualizations and plugins.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Unified Robot Description Format (URDF) is an XML file format for robot model description.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] rosbag is a command line tool used to record and playback ROS message data. rosbag uses a file format called bags, which log ROS messages by listening to topics and recording messages as they come in.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Playing messages back from a bag is largely the same as having the original nodes that produced the data in the ROS computation graph, making bags a useful tool for recording data to be used in later development.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] While rosbag is a command line only tool, rqt_bag provides a GUI interface to rosbag.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] catkin is the ROS1 build system, having replaced rosbuild as of ROS Groovy. catkin is based on CMake and is similarly cross-platform, open-source, and language-independent.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] As of ROS2 catkin is no longer in use, but still maintained for legacy support.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The rosbash package provides a suite of tools which augment the functionality of the bash shell.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] These tools include rosls, roscd, and roscp, which replicate the functionalities of ls, cd, and cp respectively.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The ROS versions of these tools allow users to use ros package names in place of the file path where the package is located.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The package also adds tab-completion to most ROS utilities and includes rosed, which edits a given file with the chosen default text editor, as well rosrun, which runs executables in ROS packages. rosbash supports the same functionalities for zsh and tcsh, to a lesser extent.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS contains many open-source implementations of common robotics functionality and algorithms.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] These open-source implementations are organized into packages.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Many packages are included as part of ROS distributions, while others may be developed by individuals and distributed through code-sharing sites such as github.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS releases may be incompatible with other releases and are often referred to by code name rather than version number.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS 2 currently releases a version every year in May, following the release of Ubuntu LTS versions.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] These releases are alternating supported for 5 years (even years/LTS Ubuntu version release) and 1.5 years (uneven years/no LTS Ubuntu version release).
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Aside from this, there has been the ROS-Industrial or ROS-I derivate project since at least 2012.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS-Industrial is an open-source project (BSD (legacy)/Apache 2.0 (preferred) license) that extends the advanced abilities of ROS to manufacturing automation and robotics.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In the industrial environment, there are two different approaches to programming a robot: either through an external proprietary controller, typically implemented using ROS, or via the respective native programming language of the robot.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS can therefore be seen as the software-based approach to programming industrial robots instead of the classic robot controller-based approach.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The ROS-Industrial repository includes interfaces for common industrial manipulators, grippers, sensors, and device networks.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] It also provides software libraries for automatic 2D/3D sensor calibration, process path/motion planning, applications like Scan-N-Plan, developer tools like the Qt Creator ROS Plugin, and training curricula that are specific to the needs of manufacturers.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] ROS-I is supported by an international Consortium of industry and research members.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The project began as a collaborative endeavor between Yaskawa Motoman Robotics, Southwest Research Institute, and Willow Garage to support the use of ROS for manufacturing automation, with the GitHub repository being founded in January 2012 by Shaun Edwards (SwRI).
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The Consortia supports the global ROS-Industrial community by conducting ROS-I training, providing technical support and setting the future roadmap for ROS-I, as well as conducting pre-competitive joint industry projects to develop new ROS-I abilities.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In November 2020, NASA announced Blue Origin had been selected through the Space Technology Mission Directorate's Announcement of Collaboration Opportunity (ACO) to co-develop Space Robot Operating System (Space ROS) together with three NASA centers.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The purpose of Space ROS is to provide a reusable and modular software framework for robotic and autonomous space systems predicated on ROS 2 that is compliant to aerospace mission and safety assurance requirements (such as NPR 7150.2 and DO-178C).
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] The project was formulated and led by Will Chambers, Blue Origin's principal technologist of robotics at the time.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] In 2021, Blue Origin subcontracted software development workload to Open Robotics who remained on the team until the program ended in 2022.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] Space ROS is currently an open community project.
[src:robotics/robot-operating-system] PickNik Robotics and Open Source Robotics Foundation currently lead the Space ROS effort.
[src:robotics/robotics] The goal of most robotics is to design machines that can assist humans in various fields, such as agriculture, construction, domestic work, food processing, inventory management, manufacturing, medicine, military, mining, space exploration, and transportation.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robots impact humans by displacing workers.
[src:robotics/robotics] Some expect this to occur at an increasing rate, leading to proposed solutions such as basic income.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robotics is itself a lucrative business that creates careers, especially for postgraduates.
[src:robotics/robotics] Roboticists often aim to create machines that seem to interface naturally with humans.
[src:robotics/robotics] The field is under active research and development, with areas of interest including robot kinematics and quantum robotics.
[src:robotics/robotics] Many different types of batteries can be used as a power source.
[src:robotics/robotics] Most are lead–acid batteries, which are safe and have relatively long shelf lives but are rather heavy compared to silver–cadmium batteries, which are much smaller in volume and much more expensive.
[src:robotics/robotics] Designing a battery-powered robot needs to take into account factors such as safety, cycle lifetime, and weight.
[src:robotics/robotics] Generators, often some type of internal combustion engine, can also be used, but are often mechanically complex and inefficient.
[src:robotics/robotics] Additionally, a tether could connect the robot to a power supply, saving weight and space, but requiring a cumbersome cable.
[src:robotics/robotics] Actuators are the "muscles" of a robot, the parts which convert stored energy into movement.
[src:robotics/robotics] The most popular actuators are electric motors that rotate a wheel or gear and linear actuators that control factory robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] Most robots use electric motors—often brushed and brushless DC motors in portable robots or AC motors in industrial robots and computer numerical control machines—especially in systems with lighter loads and where the predominant form of motion is rotational.
[src:robotics/robotics] Meanwhile, linear actuators move in and out and often have quicker direction changes, particularly when large forces are needed, such as with industrial robotics.
[src:robotics/robotics] They are typically powered by oil or compressed air, but can also be powered by electricity, usually via a motor and a leadscrew.
[src:robotics/robotics] The mechanical rack and pinion is common.
[src:robotics/robotics] Recent alternatives to DC motors are piezoelectric motors, including ultrasonic motors, in which tiny piezoceramic elements vibrate many thousands of times per second, causing linear or rotary motion.
[src:robotics/robotics] One type uses the vibration of the piezo elements to step the motor in a circle or a straight line; another type uses the piezo elements to vibrate a nut or drive a screw.
[src:robotics/robotics] The advantages of these motors are nanometer resolution, speed, and force for their size.
[src:robotics/robotics] Series elastic actuation (SEA) relies on introducing intentional elasticity between the motor actuator and the load for robust force control.
[src:robotics/robotics] Due to the resultant lower reflected inertia, series elastic actuation improves safety during robot interactions or collisions.
[src:robotics/robotics] Further, it provides energy efficiency and shock absorption (mechanical filtering) while reducing excessive wear on the transmission and other components.
[src:robotics/robotics] This approach has successfully been employed in various robots, particularly advanced manufacturing robots and walking humanoid robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] The controller design of a series elastic actuator is most often performed within the passivity framework as it ensures the safety of interaction with unstructured environments.
[src:robotics/robotics] However, this framework suffers from stringent limitations imposed on the controller, which may impact performance.
[src:robotics/robotics] Pneumatic artificial muscles, also known as air muscles, are special tubes that expand (typically up to 42%) when air is forced inside them; they are used in some robot applications.
[src:robotics/robotics] Muscle wire, also known as shape memory alloy, is a material that contracts (under 5%) when electricity is applied; they have been used for some small robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] Electroactive polymers are a plastic material that can contract substantially (up to 380% activation strain) from electricity and have been used in the facial muscles and arms of humanoid robots, as well as to enable new robots to float, fly, swim or walk.
[src:robotics/robotics] Additionally, elastic carbon nanotubes are a promising experimental artificial muscle technology.
[src:robotics/robotics] The absence of defects in carbon nanotubes enables these filaments to deform elastically by several percent, with energy storage levels of perhaps 10 J/cm3 for metal nanotubes.
[src:robotics/robotics] Human biceps could be replaced with wire of this material measuring 8 millimetres (3⁄8 in) in diameter, feasibly allowing future robots to outperform humans.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robots with only one or two wheel(s) can have advantages such as greater efficiency, reduced parts, and navigation through confined areas.
[src:robotics/robotics] A one-wheeled robot balances on a round ball; Carnegie Mellon University's Ballbot is the approximate height and width of a person.
[src:robotics/robotics] Several attempts have also been made to build spherical robots (also known as orb bots or ball bots), which move by spinning a weight inside the ball or rotating outer shells.
[src:robotics/robotics] Two-wheeled balancing robots generally use a gyroscope to detect how much a robot is falling and drive the wheels proportionally up to hundreds of times per second to counterbalance the fall, based on inverted pendulum dynamics.
[src:robotics/robotics] NASA's Robonaut has been mounted to a Segway for a similar effect.
[src:robotics/robotics] Most mobile robots have four wheels or continuous tracks.
[src:robotics/robotics] Six wheels can give better traction in outdoor terrain, while tracks provide even more grip.
[src:robotics/robotics] Tracked wheels are common for outdoor off-road robots, but are difficult to use indoors.
[src:robotics/robotics] A small number of skating robots have been developed, one of which is a multimodal walking and skating device with four legs and unpowered wheels.
[src:robotics/robotics] Several robots have been made that can walk on two legs, but not yet as reliably as a human.
[src:robotics/robotics] Many other robots have been built that walk on more than two legs, being significantly easier.
[src:robotics/robotics] Walking robots could be used for uneven terrains, providing a high degree of mobility and efficiency, but two-legged robots can currently only handle flat floors or perhaps stairs.
[src:robotics/robotics] A modern passenger airliner is essentially a flying robot, with two humans to manage it.
[src:robotics/robotics] The autopilot can control the plane through takeoff, normal flight, and landing.
[src:robotics/robotics] Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) can be smaller and lighter and fly into dangerous territory for military use, perhaps even being triggered to fire automatically.
[src:robotics/robotics] Other flying robots include cruise missiles, the entomopter, and the Epson micro helicopter robot.
[src:robotics/robotics] Additionally, some lighter-than-air robots are propelled by paddles and guided by sonar.
[src:robotics/robotics] Biomimetic flying robots (BFRs) take inspiration from flying mammals, birds, or insects.
[src:robotics/robotics] They can have flapping wings, which generate the lift and thrust, or they can be propeller-actuated.
[src:robotics/robotics] Flapping-wing designs have increased maneuverability and reduced energy consumption compared to propeller actuation.
[src:robotics/robotics] BFRs inspired by mammals and birds share similar flight characteristics and design considerations.
[src:robotics/robotics] For instance, they minimize edge fluttering and pressure-induced wingtip curl by increasing the rigidity of the wing edge.
[src:robotics/robotics] Several different approaches have been used to develop robots that have the ability to climb vertical surfaces.
[src:robotics/robotics] One approach mimics the movements of a human climber on a wall with protrusions; adjusting the center of mass and moving each limb in turn to gain leverage.
[src:robotics/robotics] Another approach uses the specialized toe-pad method of wall-climbing geckoes, which can run on smooth surfaces such as vertical glass, one example being named Speedy Freelander.
[src:robotics/robotics] A third approach is to mimic the motion of a snake climbing a pole.
[src:robotics/robotics] Separately, snake robots can be used for horizontal navigation, possibly being able to search through confined spaces and navigate amphibiously.
[src:robotics/robotics] It is calculated that when swimming, some fish can achieve a propulsive efficiency greater than 90%.
[src:robotics/robotics] Furthermore, they can accelerate and maneuver far better than any man-made boat or submarine and cause less disturbance, being a desirable ability for aquatic robots, one of which models fish locomotion.
[src:robotics/robotics] One example copies the streamlined shape and propulsion of the front 'flippers' of penguins.
[src:robotics/robotics] Others emulate the locomotion of the manta ray and jellyfish.
[src:robotics/robotics] In 2013, a robotic fish outperformed some real fish in average maximum velocity and endurance.
[src:robotics/robotics] Sailboat robots, such as *Vaimos*, have been developed in order to make measurements at the surface of the ocean.
[src:robotics/robotics] Since saiboat robots are wind-propelled, the batteries only power the computer, communication and actuators (to tune the rudder and sail).
[src:robotics/robotics] Two major sailboat robot competitions occur at the Microtransat Challenge and the World Robotic Sailing Championship.
[src:robotics/robotics] A definition of robotic manipulation has been described by Matthew T.
[src:robotics/robotics] Mason as the robot's "control of its environment through selective contact".
[src:robotics/robotics] Robots need to manipulate objects; pick up, modify, destroy, move or otherwise have an effect.
[src:robotics/robotics] Thus a robotic arm is referred to as a *manipulator* and its functional end (e.g. a tool or hand) is known as an *end effector*.
[src:robotics/robotics] Most robot arms have replaceable end effectors, each allowing them to perform some small range of tasks.
[src:robotics/robotics] Some have a fixed manipulator that cannot be replaced, including highly versatile manipulators like a humanoid hand.
[src:robotics/robotics] Some of these have powerful dexterity intelligence, up to 20 degrees of freedom, and hundreds of tactile sensors.
[src:robotics/robotics] One of the most common types of end effectors are 'grippers'.
[src:robotics/robotics] In its simplest manifestation, it consists of just two fingers that can open and close to pick up and let go of small objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Fingers can be made of a chain with a metal wire running through it.
[src:robotics/robotics] Hands that resemble and work more like a human hand include the Shadow Hand and the Robonaut hand.
[src:robotics/robotics] Mechanical grippers can come in various types, including friction and encompassing jaws.
[src:robotics/robotics] Friction jaws use all the force of the gripper to hold the object in place using friction.
[src:robotics/robotics] Encompassing jaws cradle the object in place, using less friction.
[src:robotics/robotics] Suction end effectors, powered by vacuum generators, are very simple astrictive devices that can hold very large loads provided the prehension surface is smooth enough to ensure suction.
[src:robotics/robotics] Pick-and-place robots for electronic components and for large objects like car windscreens, often use very simple vacuum end effectors.
[src:robotics/robotics] Suction is a highly used type of end effector in industry, in part because the natural compliance of soft suction end effectors can be less likely to damage objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] The mechanical structure of a robot must be controlled to perform tasks.
[src:robotics/robotics] The control of a robot involves three distinct phases – perception, processing, and action (robotic paradigms).
[src:robotics/robotics] Sensors give information about the environment or the robot itself (e.g. the position of its joints or its end effector).
[src:robotics/robotics] This information is then processed to be stored or transmitted and to calculate the appropriate signals to the actuators (motors), which move the mechanical structure to achieve the required coordinated motion or force actions.
[src:robotics/robotics] The processing phase can range in complexity.
[src:robotics/robotics] At a reactive level, it may translate raw sensor information directly into actuator commands (e.g. firing motor power electronic gates based directly upon encoder feedback signals to achieve the required torque/velocity of the shaft).
[src:robotics/robotics] Sensor fusion and internal models may first be used to estimate parameters of interest (e.g. the position of the robot's gripper) from noisy sensor data.
[src:robotics/robotics] An immediate task (such as moving the gripper in a certain direction until an object is detected with a proximity sensor) is sometimes inferred from these estimates.
[src:robotics/robotics] Techniques from control theory are generally used to convert the higher-level tasks into individual commands that drive the actuators, most often using kinematic and dynamic models of the mechanical structure.
[src:robotics/robotics] At longer time scales or with more sophisticated tasks, the robot may need to build and reason with a cognitive model, which try to represent the robot, the world, and how the two interact.
[src:robotics/robotics] Pattern recognition and computer vision can be used to track objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Mapping, motion planning and other AI techniques may be used to figure out how to act and avoid obstacles.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robotic control systems integrate multiple sensors and effectors, have many interacting degrees of freedom and require operator interfaces, programming tools and real-time capabilities.
[src:robotics/robotics] They are often connected to wider communication networks, including the Internet of things, a network correlating physical objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Progress towards open architecture, layered, user-friendly and 'intelligent' sensor-based interconnected robots has emerged from earlier concepts related to flexible manufacturing systems.
[src:robotics/robotics] Further, several 'open or 'hybrid' reference architectures provide advantages over prior 'closed' robot control systems.
[src:robotics/robotics] Open-architecture controllers are said to be better able to meet the growing requirements of a wide range of robot users, including system developers, end users and research scientists, and are better positioned to contribute advanced industrial concepts.
[src:robotics/robotics] When implemented in real time, such techniques can potentially enable more adaptive control systems when working in unfamiliar environments.
[src:robotics/robotics] Generic reference architecture and associated interconnected, open-architecture robot and controller implementation has been used in a number of studies.
[src:robotics/robotics] Sensors allow robots to receive information about the environment or internal components.
[src:robotics/robotics] This is essential for robots to perform their tasks and respond to changes with the appropriate response.
[src:robotics/robotics] Sensors are used for various forms of measurements, to provide real-time information, and to give the robots warnings; they can include cameras and microphones, as well as those that monitor network signals, power level, pressure, and temperature.
[src:robotics/robotics] Current robotic and prosthetic hands receive far less tactile information than the human hand.
[src:robotics/robotics] Recent research has developed a tactile sensor array that mimics the mechanical properties and touch receptors of human fingertips.
[src:robotics/robotics] The sensor array is constructed as a rigid core surrounded by conductive fluid contained by an elastomeric skin.
[src:robotics/robotics] Electrodes are mounted on the surface of the rigid core and connected to an impedance-measuring device within the core.
[src:robotics/robotics] When the artificial skin touches an object, the fluid path around the electrodes is deformed, producing impedance changes that map the forces received from the object.
[src:robotics/robotics] An important function of artificial fingertips will likely be adjusting the grip on held objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Scientists from several European countries and Israel developed a prosthetic hand in 2009 which functions like a real one—allowing patients to write, type on a keyboard, and perform other fine movements.
[src:robotics/robotics] The prosthesis has sensors which enable the patient to sense through its fingertips.
[src:robotics/robotics] Other common forms of sensing in robotics use lidar, radar, and sonar.
[src:robotics/robotics] Lidar measures the distance to a target by illuminating the target with laser light and measuring the reflected light with a sensor.
[src:robotics/robotics] Radar uses radio waves to determine the range, angle, or velocity of objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Sonar uses sound propagation to navigate, communicate with or detect objects on or under the surface of the water.
[src:robotics/robotics] More abstractly, robot forms inspired by origami are designed to sense and analyze in extreme environments.
[src:robotics/robotics] Cameras can capture visible light and other forms of electromagnetic radiation such as infrared.
[src:robotics/robotics] Multiple sensors and particular lenses may be used to achieve a certain field of view and depth perception.
[src:robotics/robotics] Computer-vision has increasingly utilized machine learning.
[src:robotics/robotics] Barcode scanning may be utilized, but is not necessarily universally effective.
[src:robotics/robotics] A program is how a robot decides when or how to do something.
[src:robotics/robotics] Specific motions can be designed via computer animation software such as Autodesk Maya.
[src:robotics/robotics] Programs can be run by remote control, AI, or a hybrid of the two.
[src:robotics/robotics] A robot with remote-control programming, possibly operated by haptic or teleoperated devices, has a preexisting set of commands that it will perform when it receives a signal from a control source—essentially a form of automation that humans have extensive control over.
[src:robotics/robotics] Meanwhile, AI-supported autonomous robots operate without a control source and use their programming to determine responses to various stimuli.
[src:robotics/robotics] Highly predictable machines, such as industrial robots, typically do not require complex cognition.
[src:robotics/robotics] Hybrid robots may be assisted by an operator who selects certain modes or commands general actions, with AI determining the necessary motions.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robots that can operate autonomously in a dynamic environment require a combination of mapping and navigation hardware and software to traverse their environment and avoid colliding with other objects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Besides humanoids such as ASIMO and Meinü robots, this particularly applies to self-driving cars, which variously employ the Global Positioning System (GPS), radar, lidar, cameras, an inertial navigation system and/or swarms of autonomous robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] For effective use in domestic environments, the way robots receive commands should be intuitive even for people with no technological skillset.
[src:robotics/robotics] Science-fiction authors and futurists often envision humans communicating with robots via speech, gestures, and facial expressions rather than a command-line interface.
[src:robotics/robotics] Studies have shown that, for some people, interacting with a robot or imagining doing so can reduce negative feelings they may have about robots, but this can also bolster strong negative prejudices.
[src:robotics/robotics] Researchers are trying to create robots that demonstrate personality, regardless of whether this is desirable in commercial machines.
[src:robotics/robotics] Sounds, facial expressions, and body language can be used to convey emotions, e.g. in the toy robot dinosaur Pleo (c.
[src:robotics/robotics] Further, robots may incorporate awareness of personal space to their interactions.
[src:robotics/robotics] Other hurdles exist when a voice is used to interact with humans.
[src:robotics/robotics] For social reasons, synthetic voice proves suboptimal as a communication medium, making it necessary to develop the emotional component of robotic voice through various techniques.
[src:robotics/robotics] One of the earliest examples is a teaching robot developed in 1974 by Michael J.
[src:robotics/robotics] Freeman, who converted digital memory to rudimentary verbal speech via pre-recorded computer discs.
[src:robotics/robotics] Freeman's robot was programmed to teach students in The Bronx, New York.
[src:robotics/robotics] Meanwhile, recognizing human speech in real time is a difficult task for a computer, mostly because of speech's great variability.
[src:robotics/robotics] The sound of a word can vary greatly depending on accent, acoustics, volume, the previous word spoken, and the speaker's health.
[src:robotics/robotics] Strides have been made in the field since the first "voice input system" was designed in 1952.
[src:robotics/robotics] By the end of the 20th century, the best systems could recognize continuous, natural speech up to 160 words per minute with 95% accuracy.
[src:robotics/robotics] AI-assisted machines can use voice to identify emotions.
[src:robotics/robotics] Social robots will likely need to be able to recognize gestures (and perhaps perform them) to assist verbal communication.
[src:robotics/robotics] The processing and simulation of emotions by AI is known as *affective computing*.
[src:robotics/robotics] A robot should be able to interact with a human appropriately based upon their facial expressions and body language.
[src:robotics/robotics] Expressive synthetic faces have been constructed by Hanson Robotics using an elastic polymer (rubber) skin mesh animated by subsurface motors (servos), which are in turn embedded on a metal skull.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robots like Kismet can produce a range of facial expressions, enabling engagement in meaningful social exchanges.
[src:robotics/robotics] The interactive Robin the Robot similarly uses AI-based analysis and displays emotions to try to overcome exhibitions of stress and anxiety.
[src:robotics/robotics] The incorporation of robots into industries has increased efficiency and productivity.
[src:robotics/robotics] It is typically seen as a long-term investment for benefactors and perhaps even an essential component of manufacturing.
[src:robotics/robotics] However, it has the potential of replacing most of the work performed by humans, with a 2017 study finding that automation alone puts 47% of US jobs at eventual risk.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robotics is thus often used as an argument for basic income to replace lost wages.
[src:robotics/robotics] As of 2022, China had the greatest number of industrial robots in operation with 1.5 million units and was increasing that figure by more than 20% annually.
[src:robotics/robotics] The spread of robotics presents both opportunities and challenges for occupational safety and health (OSH).
[src:robotics/robotics] Despite lost wages, the substitution of people working in unhealthy or dangerous environments is an OSH benefit.
[src:robotics/robotics] This not only includes high-risk jobs in space, security, and energy, but also dirty or unsafe work in logistics, maintenance, and inspection that requires exposure to physical and/or psychosocial risks, including those stemming from repetitive or monotonous tasks better suited to machines.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robots are likely to gradually replace such jobs in other sectors like agriculture, cleaning, construction, firefighting, healthcare, and transportation.
[src:robotics/robotics] On the other hand, humans are better suited than machines for light-duty jobs involving various levels of creativity, decision-making, and flexibility.
[src:robotics/robotics] Humans and robots increasingly work in parallel within their areas of expertise.
[src:robotics/robotics] The need to work safely in a close space has resulted in *cobots* (collaborative robots).
[src:robotics/robotics] Some European countries are including robotics in their national programs, promoting healthy cooperation between robots and operators to increase productivity.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robotics is an interdisciplinary field, primarily combining mechanical engineering and computer science but also drawing on electronic engineering and other subjects.
[src:robotics/robotics] Undergraduate degrees are usually obtained in one of these subjects prior to the pursuance of a graduate degree in robotics.
[src:robotics/robotics] Robotics engineers design and maintain robots, develop new applications, and conduct research.
[src:robotics/robotics] As of 2011, the number of robotics-related jobs was steadily rising as factories increasingly utilized robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] According to a September 2021 GlobalData report, the robotics industry was worth USD $45 billion in 2020, and by 2030 it will have grown at a compound annual growth rate of 29% to $568 bn, driving jobs in robotics and related industries.
[src:robotics/robotics] Much of the research in robotics focuses not on specific industrial tasks, but on investigations into new types of robots, alternative ways to think about or design robots, and new ways to manufacture them.
[src:robotics/robotics] In 1997, Professor Hans Moravec, principal research scientist at the Carnegie's Robotics Institute, predicted that robot intelligence would reach the capacity of a lizard by 2010, a mouse by 2020, then a monkey and finally a human by around 2045.
[src:robotics/robotics] The study of motion can be divided into kinematics and dynamics.
[src:robotics/robotics] Direct or forward kinematics refers to the manual control of joints to manipulate end effectors, while in inverse kinematics, end-effector states are predetermined and the joint values automated.
[src:robotics/robotics] Kinematics encompasses calculation efficiency, collision avoidance, and stalling prevention.
[src:robotics/robotics] Meanwhile, dynamics are used to study the effect of forces upon given kinematic motions.
[src:robotics/robotics] Direct dynamics refers to the calculation of accelerations once the applied forces are known, used in computer simulations.
[src:robotics/robotics] *Inverse dynamics* refers to the calculation of the actuator forces that result in certain end-effector accelerations.
[src:robotics/robotics] Open-source robotics research seeks standards for defining, and methods for designing and building, robots so that they can easily be reproduced by anyone.
[src:robotics/robotics] Research includes legal and technical definitions; seeking out alternative tools and materials to reduce costs and simplify builds; and creating interfaces and standards for designs to work together.
[src:robotics/robotics] Human usability research also investigates how to best document builds through visual, text or video instructions.
[src:robotics/robotics] Bionics and biomimetics apply the physiology and methods of locomotion of animals to the design of robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] For example, the design of BionicKangaroo was based on the way kangaroos jump.
[src:robotics/robotics] Swarm robotics is an approach to the coordination of multiple robots as a system which consist of large numbers of mostly simple physical robots.
[src:robotics/robotics] Quantum robotics is the study of running robotic programs on quantum computers, which will likely outperform digital computers.
[src:robotics/robotics] Additional general areas of study include cobots, drones, and nanorobots.
[src:robotics/robotics] Two major academic conferences for robotics research are the International Conference on Robotics and Automation and International Conference on Intelligent Robots and Systems.
[src:robotics/servomotor] A **servomotor** (or **servo motor** or simply **servo**) is a rotary or linear actuator that allows precise control of angular or linear position, velocity, and acceleration in a mechanical system.
[src:robotics/servomotor] It constitutes part of a servomechanism, and consists of a motor coupled to a sensor (for position feedback) and a controller (often a dedicated module designed for servomotors).
[src:robotics/servomotor] Servomotors are not a specific class of motor, although the term *servomotor* is often used to describe a motor suitable for use in a closed-loop control system.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Servomotors are used in robotics, CNC machinery, and automated manufacturing.
[src:robotics/servomotor] NEMA ICS 16 defines several flange mounting patterns and corresponding bolt circles that are defined in millimeters or inches.
[src:robotics/servomotor] A servomotor is a closed-loop servomechanism that uses position feedback (either linear or angular position) to control its motion and final position.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The input to its control is a signal (either analog or digital) representing the desired position of the output shaft.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The motor is paired with a position encoder to provide position feedback (and potentially also speed feedback).
[src:robotics/servomotor] The controller compares the measured position with the desired position to generate an error signal, which when fed back causes the motor to rotate in the direction needed to bring the shaft to the desired position.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The error signal falls to zero as the desired position is approached, stopping the motor.
[src:robotics/servomotor] A simple servomotor uses position-only sensing via a potentiometer and bang-bang control of the motor, which only rotates at full speed or is stopped.
[src:robotics/servomotor] This type of servomotor is not widely used in industrial motion control, but it forms the basis of the cheap servos in radio-controlled models.
[src:robotics/servomotor] More sophisticated servomotors make use of an absolute encoder (a type of rotary encoder) to calculate the shaft's position and infer the speed of the output shaft.
[src:robotics/servomotor] A variable-speed drive is used to control the motor speed.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Both of these enhancements, usually in combination with a PID control algorithm, allow the servomotor to be brought to its commanded position more quickly and more precisely, with less overshooting.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Servomotors are generally used as a high-performance alternative to the stepper motor.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Stepper motors have some inherent ability to control position, as they have built-in output steps.
[src:robotics/servomotor] This often allows them to be used as an open-loop position control, without any feedback encoder, as their drive signal specifies the number of steps of movement to rotate, but for this, the controller needs to 'know' the position of the stepper motor on power up.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Therefore, on the first power-up, the controller will have to activate the stepper motor and turn it to a known position, e.g. until it activates an end limit switch.
[src:robotics/servomotor] This can be observed when switching on an inkjet printer; the controller will move the ink jet carrier to the extreme left and right to establish the end positions.
[src:robotics/servomotor] A servomotor can immediately turn to whatever angle the controller instructs it to, regardless of the initial position at power up, if an absolute encoder is used.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The lack of feedback of a stepper motor limits its performance, as the stepper motor can only drive a load that is well within its capacity, otherwise missed steps under load may lead to positioning errors and the system may have to be restarted or recalibrated.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The encoder and controller of a servomotor are an additional cost, but they optimize the performance of the overall system (for all of speed, power, and accuracy) relative to the capacity of the basic motor.
[src:robotics/servomotor] With larger systems, where a powerful motor represents an increasing proportion of the system cost, servomotors have the advantage.
[src:robotics/servomotor] There has been increasing popularity in closed-loop stepper motors in recent years.
[src:robotics/servomotor] They act like servomotors but have some differences in their software control to get smooth motion.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The main benefit of an open-loop stepper motor is its relatively low cost.
[src:robotics/servomotor] There is also no need to tune the feedback controller on an open-loop stepper system.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The first servomotors were developed with synchros as their encoders.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Much work was done with these systems in the development of radar and anti-aircraft artillery during World War II.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Simple servomotors may use resistive potentiometers as their position encoder.
[src:robotics/servomotor] These are only used at the very simplest and cheapest level and are in close competition with stepper motors.
[src:robotics/servomotor] They suffer from wear and electrical noise in the potentiometer track.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Although it would be possible to electrically differentiate their position signal to obtain a speed signal, PID controllers that can make use of such a speed signal generally warrant a more precise encoder.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Modern servomotors use rotary encoders, either absolute or incremental.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Absolute encoders can determine their position at power-on but are more complicated and expensive.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Incremental encoders are simpler, cheaper, and work at faster speeds.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Incremental systems, like stepper motors, often combine their inherent ability to measure intervals of rotation with a simple zero-position sensor to set their position at start-up.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Instead of servomotors, sometimes a motor with a separate, external linear encoder is used.
[src:robotics/servomotor] These motor + linear encoder systems avoid inaccuracies in the drivetrain between the motor and linear carriage, but their design is made more complicated as they are no longer a pre-packaged factory-made system.
[src:robotics/servomotor] The type of motor is not critical to a servomotor, and different types may be used.
[src:robotics/servomotor] At the simplest, brushed permanent magnet DC motors are used, owing to their simplicity and low cost.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Small industrial servomotors are typically electronically commutated brushless motors.
[src:robotics/servomotor] For large industrial servomotors, AC induction motors are typically used, often with variable frequency drives to allow control of their speed.
[src:robotics/servomotor] For ultimate performance in a compact package, brushless AC motors with permanent magnet fields are used, effectively large versions of Brushless DC electric motors.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Drive modules for servomotors are a standard industrial component.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Their design is a branch of power electronics, usually based on a three-phase MOSFET or IGBT H bridge.
[src:robotics/servomotor] These standard modules accept a single direction and pulse count (rotation distance) as input.
[src:robotics/servomotor] They may also include over-temperature monitoring, over-torque, and stall detection features.
[src:robotics/servomotor] As the encoder type, gearhead ratio, and overall system dynamics are application specific, it is more difficult to produce the overall controller as an off-the-shelf module, and so these are often implemented as part of the main controller.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Most modern servomotors are designed and supplied around a dedicated controller module from the same manufacturer.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Controllers may also be developed around microcontrollers in order to reduce cost for large-volume applications.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Modern industrial servomotor systems employ digital servo drives or amplifiers to regulate current, velocity, and position using feedback loops.
[src:robotics/servomotor] These drives communicate over industrial fieldbuses such as EtherCAT, CANopen, and POWERLINK, allowing coordinated motion among multiple axes.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Manufacturers including ADVANCED Motion Controls, Bosch Rexroth, and Yaskawa have developed such servo-drive families used in robotics, CNC machinery, and automated production equipment.
[src:robotics/servomotor] Integrated servomotors are designed to include the motor, driver, encoder, and associated electronics into a single package.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] SLAM algorithms are tailored to the available resources and are not aimed at perfection but at operational compliance.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Published approaches are employed in self-driving cars, unmanned aerial vehicles, autonomous underwater vehicles, planetary rovers, newer domestic robots and even inside the human body.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Given a series of controls $u_{t}$ and sensor observations $o_{t}$ over discrete time steps t , the SLAM problem is to compute an estimate of the agent's state $x_{t}$ and a map of the environment $m_{t}$ .
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] where Z is the normalization constant, which ensures all the probabilities sum up to 1.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Like many inference problems, the solutions to inferring the two variables together can be found, to a local optimum solution, by alternating updates of the two beliefs in a form of an expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Statistical techniques used to approximate the above equations include Kalman filters and particle filters (the algorithm behind Monte Carlo Localization).
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] They provide an estimation of the posterior probability distribution for the pose of the robot and for the parameters of the map.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Methods which conservatively approximate the above model using covariance intersection are able to avoid reliance on statistical independence assumptions to reduce algorithmic complexity for large-scale applications.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Other approximation methods achieve improved computational efficiency by using simple bounded-region representations of uncertainty.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Set-membership techniques are mainly based on interval constraint propagation.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] They provide a set which encloses the pose of the robot and a set approximation of the map.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] MAP estimators compute the most likely explanation of the robot poses and the map given the sensor data, rather than trying to estimate the entire posterior probability.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] New SLAM algorithms remain an active research area, and are often driven by differing requirements and assumptions about the types of maps, sensors and models as detailed below.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Many SLAM systems can be viewed as combinations of choices from each of these aspects.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Topological maps are a method of environment representation which capture the connectivity (i.e., topology) of the environment rather than creating a geometrically accurate map.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Topological SLAM approaches have been used to enforce global consistency in metric SLAM algorithms.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In contrast, grid maps use arrays (typically square or hexagonal) of discretized cells to represent a topological world, and make inferences about which cells are occupied.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Typically the cells are assumed to be statistically independent to simplify computation.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Under such assumption, $P(m_{t}|x_{t},m_{t-1},o_{t})$ are set to 1 if the new map's cells are consistent with the observation $o_{t}$ at location $x_{t}$ and 0 if inconsistent.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Modern self driving cars mostly simplify the mapping problem to almost nothing, by making extensive use of highly detailed map data collected in advance.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] This can include map annotations to the level of marking locations of individual white line segments and curbs on the road.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Location-tagged visual data such as Google's StreetView may also be used as part of maps.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Essentially such systems simplify the SLAM problem to a simpler localization only task, perhaps allowing for moving objects such as cars and people only to be updated in the map at runtime.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] SLAM will always use several different types of sensors, and the powers and limits of various sensor types have been a major driver of new algorithms.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Statistical independence is the mandatory requirement to cope with metric bias and with noise in measurements.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Different types of sensors give rise to different SLAM algorithms which assumptions are most appropriate to the sensors.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] At one extreme, laser scans or visual features provide details of many points within an area, sometimes rendering SLAM inference unnecessary because shapes in these point clouds can be easily and unambiguously aligned at each step via image registration.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] At the opposite extreme, tactile sensors are extremely sparse as they contain only information about points very close to the agent, so they require strong prior models to compensate in purely tactile SLAM.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Most practical SLAM tasks fall somewhere between these visual and tactile extremes.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Sensor models divide broadly into landmark-based and raw-data approaches.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Landmarks are uniquely identifiable objects in the world which location can be estimated by a sensor, such as Wi-Fi access points or radio beacons.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Raw-data approaches make no assumption that landmarks can be identified, and instead model $P(o_{t}|x_{t})$ directly as a function of the location.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Optical sensors may be one-dimensional (single beam) or 2D- (sweeping) laser rangefinders, 3D high definition light detection and ranging (lidar), 3D flash lidar, 2D or 3D sonar sensors, and one or more 2D cameras.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Since the invention of local features, such as SIFT, there has been intense research into visual SLAM (VSLAM) using primarily visual (camera) sensors, because of the increasing ubiquity of cameras such as those in mobile devices.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Both visual and lidar sensors are informative enough to allow for landmark extraction in many cases.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Other recent forms of SLAM include tactile SLAM (sensing by local touch only), radar SLAM, acoustic SLAM, and Wi-Fi-SLAM (sensing by strengths of nearby Wi-Fi access points).
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Recent approaches apply quasi-optical wireless ranging for multi-lateration (real-time locating system (RTLS)) or multi-angulation in conjunction with SLAM as a tribute to erratic wireless measures.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] A kind of SLAM for human pedestrians uses a shoe mounted inertial measurement unit as the main sensor and relies on the fact that pedestrians are able to avoid walls to automatically build floor plans of buildings by an indoor positioning system.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For some outdoor applications, the need for SLAM has been almost entirely removed due to high precision differential GPS sensors.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] From a SLAM perspective, these may be viewed as location sensors which likelihoods are so sharp that they completely dominate the inference.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] However, GPS sensors may occasionally decline or go down entirely, e.g. during times of military conflict, which are of particular interest to some robotics applications.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The $P(x_{t}|x_{t-1})$ term represents the kinematics of the model, which usually include information about action commands given to a robot.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] As a part of the model, the kinematics of the robot is included, to improve estimates of sensing under conditions of inherent and ambient noise.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The dynamic model balances the contributions from various sensors, various partial error models and finally comprises in a sharp virtual depiction as a map with the location and heading of the robot as some cloud of probability.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Mapping is the final depicting of such model, the map is either such depiction or the abstract term for the model.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For 2D robots, the kinematics are usually given by a mixture of rotation and "move forward" commands, which are implemented with additional motor noise.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Unfortunately the distribution formed by independent noise in angular and linear directions is non-Gaussian, but is often approximated by a Gaussian.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An alternative approach is to ignore the kinematic term and read odometry data from robot wheels after each command—such data may then be treated as one of the sensors rather than as kinematics.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Non-static environments, such as those containing other vehicles or pedestrians, continue to present research challenges.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] SLAM with DATMO is a model which tracks moving objects in a similar way to the agent itself.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Loop closure is the problem of recognizing a previously-visited location and updating beliefs accordingly.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] This can be a problem because model or algorithm errors can assign low priors to the location.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Typical loop closure methods apply a second algorithm to compute some type of sensor measure similarity, and reset the location priors when a match is detected.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For example, this can be done by storing and comparing bag of words vectors of scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT) features from each previously visited location.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In neuroscience, the hippocampus appears to be involved in SLAM-like computations, giving rise to place cells, and has formed the basis for bio-inspired SLAM systems such as RatSLAM.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An extension of the common SLAM problem has been applied to the acoustic domain, where environments are represented by the three-dimensional (3D) position of sound sources, termed aSLAM (**A**coustic **S**imultaneous **L**ocalization and **M**apping).
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Early implementations of this technique have used direction-of-arrival (DoA) estimates of the sound source location, and rely on principal techniques of sound localization to determine source locations.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An observer, or robot must be equipped with a microphone array to enable use of Acoustic SLAM, so that DoA features are properly estimated.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Acoustic SLAM has paved foundations for further studies in acoustic scene mapping, and can play an important role in human-robot interaction through speech.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] To map multiple, and occasionally intermittent sound sources, an acoustic SLAM system uses foundations in random finite set theory to handle the varying presence of acoustic landmarks.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] However, the nature of acoustically derived features leaves Acoustic SLAM susceptible to problems of reverberation, inactivity, and noise within an environment.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Originally designed for human–robot interaction, Audio-Visual SLAM is a framework that provides the fusion of landmark features obtained from both the acoustic and visual modalities within an environment.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Human interaction is characterized by features perceived in not only the visual modality, but the acoustic modality as well; as such, SLAM algorithms for human-centered robots and machines must account for both sets of features.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An Audio-Visual framework estimates and maps positions of human landmarks through use of visual features like human pose, and audio features like human speech, and fuses the beliefs for a more robust map of the environment.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For applications in mobile robotics (ex. drones, service robots), it is valuable to use low-power, lightweight equipment such as monocular cameras, or microelectronic microphone arrays.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Audio-Visual SLAM can also allow for complimentary function of such sensors, by compensating the narrow field-of-view, feature occlusions, and optical degradations common to lightweight visual sensors with the full field-of-view, and unobstructed feature representations inherent to audio sensors.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The susceptibility of audio sensors to reverberation, sound source inactivity, and noise can also be accordingly compensated through fusion of landmark beliefs from the visual modality.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Complimentary function between the audio and visual modalities in an environment can prove valuable for the creation of robotics and machines that fully interact with human speech and human movement.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Various SLAM algorithms are implemented in the open-source software Robot Operating System (ROS) libraries, often used together with the Point Cloud Library for 3D maps or visual features from OpenCV.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In robotics, *EKF SLAM* is a class of algorithms which uses the extended Kalman filter (EKF) for SLAM.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Typically, EKF SLAM algorithms are feature based, and use the maximum likelihood algorithm for data association.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In the 1990s and 2000s, EKF SLAM had been the de facto method for SLAM, until the introduction of FastSLAM.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Associated with the EKF is the gaussian noise assumption, which significantly impairs EKF SLAM's ability to deal with uncertainty.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] With greater amount of uncertainty in the posterior, the linearization in the EKF fails.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In robotics, **GraphSLAM** is a SLAM algorithm which uses sparse information matrices produced by generating a factor graph of observation interdependencies (two observations are related if they contain data about the same landmark).
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] A seminal work in SLAM is the research of Smith and Cheeseman on the representation and estimation of spatial uncertainty in 1986.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Other pioneering work in this field was conducted by the research group of Hugh F.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Durrant-Whyte in the early 1990s. which showed that solutions to SLAM exist in the infinite data limit.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] This finding motivates the search for algorithms which are computationally tractable and approximate the solution.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The acronym SLAM was coined within the paper, "Localization of Autonomous Guided Vehicles" which first appeared in ISR in 1995.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The self-driving STANLEY and JUNIOR cars, led by Sebastian Thrun, won the DARPA Grand Challenge and came second in the DARPA Urban Challenge in the 2000s, and included SLAM systems, bringing SLAM to worldwide attention.
[src:robotics/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Mass-market SLAM implementations can now be found in consumer robot vacuum cleaners and virtual reality headsets such as the Meta Quest 2 and PICO 4 for markerless inside-out tracking.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A **stepper motor**, also known as **step motor** or **stepping motor**, is a brushless DC electric motor that rotates in a series of small and discrete angular steps.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Stepper motors can be set to any given step position without needing a position sensor for feedback.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The step position can be rapidly increased or decreased to create continuous rotation, or the motor can be ordered to actively hold its position at one given step.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Motors vary in size, speed, step resolution, and torque.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Switched reluctance motors are very large stepping motors with a reduced pole count.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] They generally employ closed-loop commutators.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Brushed DC motors rotate continuously when DC voltage is applied to their terminals.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The stepper motor is known for its property of converting a train of input pulses (typically square waves) into a precisely defined increment in the shaft’s rotational position.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Each pulse rotates the shaft through a fixed angle.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Stepper motors effectively have multiple "toothed" electromagnets arranged as a stator around a central rotor, a gear-shaped piece of iron.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The electromagnets are energized by an external driver circuit or a micro controller.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] To make the motor shaft turn, one electromagnet is first given power, which magnetically attracts the gear's teeth.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] When the gear's teeth are aligned to the first electromagnet, they are slightly offset from the next electromagnet.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This means that when the next electromagnet is turned on and the first is turned off, the gear rotates slightly to align with the next one.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Each of the partial rotations is called a "step", with an integer number of steps making a full rotation.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] In that way, the motor can be turned by a precise angle.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The circular arrangement of electromagnets is divided into groups, each group called a phase, and there is an equal number of electromagnets per group.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The number of groups is chosen by the designer of the stepper motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The electromagnets of each group are interleaved with the electromagnets of other groups to form a uniform pattern of arrangement.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] For example, if the stepper motor has two groups identified as A or B, and ten electromagnets in total, then the grouping pattern would be ABABABABAB.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Electromagnets within the same group are all energized together.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Because of this, stepper motors with more phases typically have more wires (or leads) to control the motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] There are three main types of stepper motors: permanent magnet, variable reluctance, and hybrid synchronous.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Permanent magnet motors use a permanent magnet (PM) in the rotor and operate on the attraction or repulsion between the rotor magnet and the stator electromagnets.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Pulses move the rotor clockwise or anticlockwise in discrete steps.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] If left powered at a final step, a strong detent remains at that shaft location.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This detent has a predictable spring rate and specified torque limit; slippage occurs if the limit is exceeded.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] If current is removed, a lesser detent still remains, holding shaft position against spring or other torque influences.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Stepping can then be resumed while reliably being synchronized with control electronics.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Permanent magnet stepper motors have simple DC switching electronics, a power-off detent, and no position readout.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] These qualities are ideal for applications such as paper printers, 3D printers, and robotics.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Such applications track position simply by counting the number of steps that each motor has been instructed to take.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Variable reluctance (VR) motors have a soft iron rotor and operate based on the principle that minimum reluctance occurs with minimum gap, so the rotor points are attracted toward the stator's magnetic poles.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Variable reluctance motors have detents when powered on, but not when powered off.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Hybrid synchronous motors are a combination of the permanent magnet and variable reluctance types, to maximize power in a small size.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] There are two basic winding arrangements for the electromagnetic coils in a two phase stepper motor: bipolar and unipolar.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A unipolar stepper motor has one winding with center tap per phase.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Each section of windings is switched on for each direction of magnetic field.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Since in this arrangement a magnetic pole can be reversed without switching the polarity of the common wire, the commutation circuit can be simply a single switching transistor for each half winding.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Typically, given a phase, the center tap of each winding is made common: three leads per phase and six leads for a typical two phase motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Often, these two phase commons are internally joined, so the motor has only five leads.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A microcontroller or stepper motor controller can be used to activate the drive transistors in the right order, and this ease of operation makes unipolar motors popular with hobbyists; they are probably the cheapest way to get precise angular movements.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] For the experimenter, the windings can be identified by touching the terminal wires together in PM motors.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] If the terminals of a coil are connected, the shaft becomes harder to turn.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] One way to distinguish the center tap (common wire) from a coil-end wire is by measuring the resistance.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Resistance between common wire and coil-end wire is always half of the resistance between coil-end wires.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This is because there is twice the length of coil between the ends and only half from center (common wire) to the end.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A quick way to determine if the stepper motor is working is to short circuit every two pairs and try turning the shaft.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Whenever a higher-than-normal resistance is felt, it indicates that the circuit to the particular winding is closed and that the phase is working.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Bipolar motors have a pair of single winding connections per phase.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The current in a winding needs to be reversed in order to reverse a magnetic pole, so the driving circuit must be more complicated, typically with an H-bridge arrangement (however there are several off-the-shelf driver chips available to make this a simple affair).
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] There are two leads per phase, none is common.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A typical driving pattern for a two coil bipolar stepper motor would be: A+ B+ A− B−.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Static friction effects using an H-bridge have been observed with certain drive topologies.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Dithering the stepper signal at a higher frequency than the motor can respond to will reduce this "static friction" effect.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Because windings are better utilized, they are more powerful than a unipolar motor of the same weight.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This is due to the physical space occupied by the windings.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A unipolar motor has twice the amount of wire in the same space, but only half used at any point in time, hence is 50% efficient (or approximately 70% of the torque output available).
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Though a bipolar stepper motor is more complicated to drive, the abundance of driver chips means this is much less difficult to achieve.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] An 8-lead stepper is like a unipolar stepper, but the leads are not joined to common internally to the motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Multi-phase stepper motors with many phases tend to have much lower levels of vibration.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] While they are more expensive, they do have a higher power density and with the appropriate drive electronics are often better suited to the application.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Stepper motor performance is strongly dependent on the driver circuit.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Torque curves may be extended to greater speeds if the stator poles can be reversed more quickly, the limiting factor being a combination of the winding inductance.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] To overcome the inductance and switch the windings quickly, one must increase the drive voltage.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This leads further to the necessity of limiting the current that these high voltages may otherwise induce.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] An additional limitation, often comparable to the effects of inductance, is the back-EMF of the motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] As the motor's rotor turns, a sinusoidal voltage is generated proportional to the speed (step rate).
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This AC voltage is subtracted from the voltage waveform available to induce a change in the current.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] L/R driver circuits are also referred to as constant voltage drives because a constant positive or negative voltage is applied to each winding to set the step positions.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] However, it is winding current, not voltage that applies torque to the stepper motor shaft.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The current I in each winding is related to the applied voltage V by the winding inductance L and the winding resistance R.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The resistance R determines the maximum current according to Ohm's law I=V/R.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The inductance L determines the maximum rate of change of the current in the winding according to the formula for an inductor dI/dt = V/L.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The resulting current for a voltage pulse is a quickly increasing current as a function of inductance.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This reaches the V/R value and holds for the remainder of the pulse.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Thus when controlled by a constant voltage drive, the maximum speed of a stepper motor is limited by its inductance since at some speed, the voltage U will be changing faster than the current I can keep up.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] In simple terms the rate of change of current is L / R (e.g. a 10 mH inductance with 2 ohms resistance will take 5 ms to reach approx 2/3 of maximum torque or around 24 ms to reach 99% of max torque).
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] To obtain high torque at high-speeds requires a large drive voltage with a low resistance and low inductance.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] With an L/R drive it is possible to control a low voltage resistive motor with a higher voltage drive simply by adding an external resistor in series with each winding.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This will waste power in the resistors, and generate heat.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] It is therefore considered a low performing option, albeit simple and cheap.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Modern voltage-mode drivers overcome some of these limitations by approximating a sinusoidal voltage waveform to the motor phases.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The amplitude of the voltage waveform is set up to increase with step rate.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] If properly tuned, this compensates the effects of inductance and back-EMF, allowing decent performance relative to current-mode drivers, but at the expense of design effort (tuning procedures) that are simpler for current-mode drivers.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Chopper drive circuits are referred to as controlled current drives because they generate a controlled current in each winding rather than applying a constant voltage.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Chopper drive circuits are most often used with two-winding bipolar motors, the two windings being driven independently to provide a specific motor torque CW or CCW.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] On each winding, a "supply" voltage is applied to the winding as a square wave voltage; example 8 kHz.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The winding inductance smooths the current which reaches a level according to the square wave duty cycle.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Most often bipolar supply (+ and - ) voltages are supplied to the controller relative to the winding return.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] So 50% duty cycle results in zero current.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] 0% results in full V/R current in one direction.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] 100% results in full current in the opposite direction.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This current level is monitored by the controller by measuring the voltage across a small sense resistor in series with the winding.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This requires additional electronics to sense winding currents, and control the switching, but it allows stepper motors to be driven with higher torque at higher speeds than L/R drives.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] It also allows the controller to output predetermined current levels rather than fixed.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Integrated electronics for this purpose are widely available.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A stepper motor is a polyphase AC synchronous motor (see Theory below), and it is ideally driven by sinusoidal current.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A full-step waveform is a gross approximation of a sinusoid, and is the reason why the motor exhibits so much vibration.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Various drive techniques have been developed to better approximate a sinusoidal drive waveform: these are half stepping and microstepping.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] In this drive method only a single phase is activated at a time.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] It has the same number of steps as the full-step drive, but the motor will have significantly less torque than rated.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The animated figure shown above is a wave drive motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] In the animation, rotor has 25 teeth and it takes 4 steps to rotate by one tooth position.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] So there will be 25 × 4 = 100 steps per full rotation and each step will be 360⁄100 = 3.6°.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This is the usual method for full-step driving the motor.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Two phases are always on so the motor will provide its maximum rated torque.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] As soon as one phase is turned off, another one is turned on.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Wave drive and single phase full step are both one and the same, with same number of steps but difference in torque.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] When half-stepping, the drive alternates between two phases on and a single phase on.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The motor also has less torque (approx 70%) at the full-step position (where only a single phase is on).
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This may be mitigated by increasing the current in the active winding to compensate.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The advantage of half stepping is that the drive electronics need not change to support it.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] In animated figure shown above, if we change it to half-stepping, then it will take 8 steps to rotate by 1 tooth position.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] So there will be 25×8 = 200 steps per full rotation and each step will be 360/200 = 1.8°.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Its angle per step is half of the full step.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] What is commonly referred to as microstepping is often *sine–cosine microstepping* in which the winding current approximates a sinusoidal AC waveform.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The common way to achieve sine-cosine current is with chopper-drive circuits.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Sine–cosine microstepping is the most common form, but other waveforms can be used.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Regardless of the waveform used, as the microsteps become smaller, motor operation becomes smoother, thereby greatly reducing resonance in any parts the motor may be connected to, as well as the motor itself.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Resolution will be limited by the mechanical stiction, backlash, and other sources of error between the motor and the end device.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Gear reducers may be used to increase resolution of positioning.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Step size reduction is an important step motor feature and a fundamental reason for their use in positioning.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Example: many modern hybrid step motors are rated such that the travel of every full step (example 1.8 degrees per full step or 200 full steps per revolution) will be within 3% or 5% of the travel of every other full step, as long as the motor is operated within its specified operating ranges.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Several manufacturers show that their motors can easily maintain the 3% or 5% equality of step travel size as step size is reduced from full stepping down to 1/10 stepping.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Then, as the microstepping divisor number grows, step size repeatability degrades.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] At large step size reductions it is possible to issue many microstep commands before any motion occurs at all and then the motion can be a "jump" to a new position.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Some stepper controller ICs use increased current to minimise such missed steps, especially when the peak current pulses in one phase would otherwise be very brief.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A step motor can be viewed as a synchronous AC motor with the number of poles (on both rotor and stator) increased, taking care that they have no common denominator.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Additionally, soft magnetic material with many teeth on the rotor and stator cheaply multiplies the number of poles (reluctance motor).
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Modern steppers are of hybrid design, having both permanent magnets and soft iron cores.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] To achieve full rated torque, the coils in a stepper motor must reach their full rated current during each step.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Winding inductance and counter-EMF generated by a moving rotor tend to resist changes in drive current, so that as the motor speeds up, less and less time is spent at full current—thus reducing motor torque.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] As speeds further increase, the current will not reach the rated value, and eventually the motor will cease to produce torque.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This is the measure of the torque produced by a stepper motor when it is operated without an acceleration state.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] At low speeds the stepper motor can synchronize itself with an applied step frequency, and this pull-in torque must overcome friction and inertia.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] It is important to make sure that the load on the motor is frictional rather than inertial as the friction reduces any unwanted oscillations.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The pull-in curve defines an area called the start/stop region.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Into this region, the motor can be started/stopped instantaneously with a load applied and without loss of synchronism.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] The stepper motor pull-out torque is measured by accelerating the motor to the desired speed and then increasing the torque loading until the motor stalls or misses steps.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] This measurement is taken across a wide range of speeds and the results are used to generate the stepper motor's dynamic performance curve.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] As noted below this curve is affected by drive voltage, drive current and current switching techniques.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] A designer may include a safety factor between the rated torque and the estimated full load torque required for the application.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Synchronous electric motors using permanent magnets have a resonant position holding torque (called detent torque or cogging, and sometimes included in the specifications) when not driven electrically.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] Soft iron reluctance cores do not exhibit this behavior.
[src:robotics/stepper-motor] When the motor moves a single step it overshoots the final resting point and oscillates round this point as it comes to rest.
